column12: Improvements in Handles or Cases for Feeler and like Gauges or Knife and other Blades.
column13: 2976. Moore, F. Feb. 5. Handles, pivoted-blade type.-A handle or case for knife and other blades and feeler and like gauges has one side piece pivoted and movable laterally in relation to the other, so that the blades &c. can be removed, replaced, or added to. The side piece A, Fig. 2, pivoted at G to the other side piece B, has a closed or open-ended slot H, which engages with the rivet C, on which the blades &c. are pivoted. The rivet is circumferentially grooved and split longitudinally so that the parts spring together when the narrow portion of the slot H is forced against the groove in the rivet, the rivet spring- ing out at the wider end of the slot and holding the two sides of the handle secure. In a modification, Fig. 6, a grooved solid rivet is used, and the material of the side piece A around the slot H is bent slightly outwards, as shown, to engage resiliently the groove in the rivet.

column13: A deer attracting device and/or a kit incorporating the same facilitates luring deer to a specific location. The device includes a base that is supported from below by an underlying ground surface and a lock that holds a visual lure in an upright position, extending away from the base, so that deer can easily see the visual lure. A scent carrier may be applied to the visual lure and is configured to entice deer to apply their own scent(s) to the visual lure by scent marking or licking the lure. This encourages other deer to do the same after being visually drawn close enough to the visual lure to detect the scent. Correspondingly, the deer maintain or replenish the scent of the lure mitigating the need for a human to artificially do the same. The visual lure is maintained in position on the base be a column within which a lower end of the visual lure is received, and a lock that maintains the visual lure within the column.

When the wrapper is folded round the pad these portions overlap and provide an impervious outer surface; while, at the same time, the tensile strength of the wrapper is appreciably increased. The strength of the securing tabs may be further increased by extending the bonding adhesive over the ends of the middle portion up to the ends 19, 20 of the pad. The central portion, which covers the upper face of the pad when in use, may further be coated with spaced lines of adhesive in order to improve the tensile strength without appreciably decreasing its permeability.

column13: A retrieving tool including a retrieving dummy and/or a kit incorporating the same is provided that facilitates training a dog or puppy to find and/or retrieve antlers that were shed by antler bearing animals. The retrieving dummy is shaped to resemble a naturally grown antler and emits an antler scent. A scent carrier may be applied to the retrieving dummy, to allow the retrieving dummy to emit such antler scent. The kit may further include a second retrieving dummy that is less similar in shape, texture, hardness or feel, to a naturally grown antler than the first, and a scent intensity of the antler scent may be varied with use of the one or more retrieving dummies so as to allow for incremental or gradual introduction of the shape, feel, and/or scent of naturally grown antlers to the dog or puppy being trained.

column12: Improvements in line feeding devices for printing apparatus
column13: 1,045,697. Selective-printing apparatus. CREED & CO. Ltd. May 20, 1964, No. 20770/64. Heading B6F. Apparatus for feeding a printing medium D in steps through a printing machine, e.g. a teleprinter, which steps may be greater or less than or equal to a line space, comprises a roller 1 around which the medium D passes, ratchet- and-pawl means 7, 8 for rotating the roller 1, an input member 23 movable from a rest position in direction A and with a fixed throw to actuate the devices 7, 8, and an interposer 37 which in the rest position of the member 23 causes the pawl 8 to be moved clear of the ratchet wheel 7. In the rest position, the roller 1 can be rotated manually by a knob 49. An extension of the shaft 4 of the roller 1 carries the ratchet wheel 7 and the knob 49. A frame 12 is pivoted on the shaft 4 and one limb 16 thereof has a lever arm 20 with notches 21 on its upper edge, one of the notches being engaged by a pin 22 on the input member 23 and the particular notch engaged determining the extent of the feed step as described below. Another limb 11 of the frame 12 carries the pawl 8 which is spring-urged towards the wheel 7. Downward movement of the input member 23 effected, e.g. electromagnetically by a signal, causes a downward movement of the pawl 8 which movement releases the pawl from a tongue 40 holding the pawl away from the wheel 8 so that the pawl 7 engages the wheel 8 and rotates the roller 1. The tongue 40 is part of the interposer 37 which is pivoted on the shaft 4 and has an arm 38 pivoted by a pin 31 to a part 28 of a lever 24 pivoted on a fixed shaft 25. The pin 31 is engaged in one of a number of notches 21 in a pivoted arm 32, these notches corresponding to the notches 21 in lever arm 20. The arms 20, 32 are biased upwardly by springs 35, 34 respectively. At the end of the lever 24 opposite to that carrying the part 28 is a forked arm 30 engaging the pin 22, and also a key portion 29. Pivoted movement of the lever 24 in the direction E, effected by manual or electromagnetic operation of the key portion 29, causes the pins 22, 31 to be moved into the next adjacent notches 21. This causes (a) lengthening of the effective length of lever arm 20 and a decrease in the throw of the pawl 8 corresponding to one tooth of wheel 7, (b) a momentary movement of the frame 12 which brings the pawl 8 adjacent to the next lower tooth of wheel 7 and (c) a movement of tongue 40 to hold the pawl 8 away from the wheel 7 in the new position of rest. As described, with the pins 22, 31 engaged with the leftward notches 21 a feed of two line spaces is obtained corresponding to four teeth of ratchet wheel 7, and rightward shift of the pins effects a reduction of half a line spacing corresponding to one tooth of ratchet wheel 7 at each step. To provide for feeds of more than two line spaces, or less than one line space, additional notches 21 would be necessary. A roller 43 mounted on a spring-urged arm 41 engages the teeth of wheel 7 to hold the wheel stationary whilst the pawl 8 is inoperative. When the shaft 4 is rotated by the knob 49, the amount of feed movement imparted to the rollers is indicated aurally by the clicks made by the roller 43 as the teeth pass over it.

column12: Novel charging pile based on new energy technology
column13: The utility model relates to the technical field of charging piles, and discloses a novel charging pile based on new energy technology, which comprises a pile body and a top cover, electric cylinders are fixedly connected to the middle parts of the inner walls of the two sides of the pile body, guide rods are fixedly connected to the top ends of the electric cylinders, and rod seats are slidably connected to the upper sides of the exteriors of the guide rods on the two sides; the ends, away from the center of the pile body, of the rod bases are fixedly connected to the inner walls of the two sides of the pile body correspondingly, the lower sides of the exteriors of the guide rods on the two sides are fixedly connected with shaft bases, and a spherical shell is arranged between the shaft bases. According to the dry powder extinguishing device, the electric cylinder extends, the guide rod ascends, the spherical shell deflects with the shaft rod as the circle center, so that the spray pipe stretches out of the pile body, then high-pressure inert gas breaks through the thin film piece and is rapidly released into the spherical shell along the air inlet pipe, and therefore dry powder extinguishing agent powder filled in the spherical shell is wrapped out of the spray pipe; and after the sealing plug is washed away, the charging host is flapped, so that the fire of the charging host is extinguished.

column13: A support plate for the internal packing of a packed column used in treatment of a fluid comprises suport elements, each resting at both ends upon ledges or the like and being generally of hat-shaped cross-section, i.e. of a generally inverted V with horizontal edge flanges. Each element has, at its end, flanged regions bent out from the body of the wall or horizontal flange respectively to form part of the periphery of an opening. Remainder lottery money intake, exclusive of lotto costs ( 29 ) and planned revenue ( 28 ), is put into a payout amount ( 30 ) for the top jackpot and the one or more base jackpots. Gaming methods ( 5 ) for determining payout proportions are determined and adjusted for maximizing lotto revenue by achieving most favorable motivation for lotto gambling. An advertising program ( 21 ) is employed for identifying a selected number plurality for an embodiment of the number-by-number lotto game with a popular item. column13: A fluid injection packing support with improved directional fluid flow characteristics, increased strength, rigidity and load carrying capacity includes a plurality of adjoining elongated hollow sections extending across a tower chamber and supported at opposite ends by a ledge fixed to the wall around the chamber. Each section has a spaced pair of inclined sidewalls diverging downwardly from an upper arched top wall portion to adjacent horizontal wall portions extending to adjoining short vertical wall portions. The inclined and horizontal wall portions have apertures with smoothly curved entrances and raised flange portions extending around and projecting to more sharply defined exit ends of the apertures which not only strengthens the wall and section but provides low resistance to the entrance and flow of the counter flowing fluids in one direction and greater resistance to the entrance and flow of the counter flowing fluids from the opposite exit ends of the apertures. Thus, the greatest part of the upwardly and downwardly moving fluids pass through separate apertures with little resistance which reduces the pressure drop across the packing support.

column13: A system for cooking spaghetti and similar pasta products includes a cooking section and a storage section with means for supplying water alternately to either section. The cooking section is equipped with a cook pot having conventional electric or gas heaters for heating water to cook spaghetti. A cooking basket containing spaghetti is suspended in the cook pot by attachment to a basket lifter. Electrical timing means connected to the basket lifter automatically lower the cooking basket at the start of a preselected cook cycle and raise the basket out of the cook pot after the cooking period has ended. The storage section includes a storage tank for rinsing and storing cooked spaghetti in cold water. Multiple rows of nesting cups stacked vertically store individual serving portions of spaghetti in the storage tank. A cup rack is used to reconstitute the spaghetti by suspending the serving cups containing cooked spaghetti in the hot water of the cook pot. The spaghetti is automatically cooked in boiling water in the cook pot and then rinsed and placed in the serving cups in individual portions for storing in cold water in the storage tank. Before serving, the spaghetti is reconstituted by placing the serving cups containing spaghetti in the cup rack on the basket lifter. The cups are lowered into the cook pot, and the spaghetti is briefly heated by hot water which is thermostatically maintained below boiling. The cup racks are then automatically raised out of the water and the heated spaghetti portions are served.

column13: PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To provide a packing element which does not cause torsion and displacement even in extreme thermal and pressure conditions, provides effective and continuous material transporting functions, and can be easily manufactured. SOLUTION: Both of a first and a second end parts in the counter sides of a metal piece are so curved as to be mutually joined and the end parts are provided with mutually linked projecting parts and recessed parts. The projecting parts of respective end parts are fitted in the recessed parts formed in the respective counterpart end parts, the metal piece is further provided with a groove hole in the middle point in approximately the middle between both end parts and also groove holes in the projecting parts of respective end parts, and a fixing and supporting material having a first and a second rim parts is installed. A tub to be fitted in the groove hole in the middle point and tubs to be fitted in the groove holes in the projecting part of the end parts are formed in the first rim part and the second rim part, respectively, and the respective tubs are deformed after inserted into the groove holes so as to retain the end parts of the metal piece and prevent the deformation of the metal piece.

The typehead 1 is displaceable vertically upwards to effect printing and is lowered to occupy the position shown in dotted outline, in Fig. 2, in the rest position. Paper and matrix carriages and supports.- The carriage 2 has slidably mounted thereon a bar 20, Fig. 1, having stub ends, each carrying a pair of half-links 18, pivotally attached with one end to cranked members 14 engaging trunnion blocks 13, carried by arms 9, to which is attached a platen bar 8. As the typehead and the carriage are rocked into printing position, the links 18 pivot the cranked members 14 clockwise until they abut stops 22, Fig. 1, whereby the arms 9 are urged anti-clockwise by a spring 11, to displace the platen bar 8 from the rest position in Fig. 2, to the printing position in Fig. 1. Paper, web feeding and guiding arrangements. The transparent printing medium 4, in Fig. 1, is guided by a roller 5, formed by a usual roller-type printing platen and the printing medium is supported by the platen bar 8 in both its rest and printing position. Printing and visual indication.-The platen bar 8 is moved into the path of the typehead to a printing position just before a printing operation is to take place and retracted immediately after, into its rest position, together with the typehead as shown in outline in Fig. 2, so that a character just printed, together with others of a line or lines of print may be projected on to a screen 29, by a light source 24, condensing lens assembly 25, transparent printing medium 4, mirrors 26 and 28 and a projector lens assembly 27. column12: Improvements in or relating to the Manufacture of Knitted Fabrics by Circular Knitting Machines
column13: 2 3 , 3 1 4. Moore, F., and Palmer, J. Oct. 20. Circular knitting-machines.-Relates to a modification of the circular rib latch-needle machine on which work in imitation of seamless fashioned hosiery may be made. The transference from rib to plain loops is effected by hand, the needlecontrolling passages being so shaped that the plain needles required for receiving the transferred rib loops are out of action while the leg is being made, and are subsequently raised into action. The heel and toe pouches are formed by splicing and slackening the loops of the heel and toe portions, the corresponding loops having been previously stiffened during the formation of the leg fabric. The heel and toe partings are imitated by one or more partial tuck courses made by special shortbutted needles. These are normally operated by a sliding portion of the clearance cam, which is depressed at the proper times out of range of the tuck-stitch needles by the action of studs or stops e<1> on a pattern chain. Another stud d determines the commencement of the heel and toe pouches by acting on a bell-crank f, which allows the splicing and loop-varying mechanisms to come into action. The stitch-cam is slidable vertically, and is operated by a slotted sliding rod h connected to the bell-crank f and carrying inclines. An horizontal crank-arm h<3> carrying screws h<4>, h<2> is continuously reciprocated by a lever i running on a rotary cam k, and according as the incline h' or depression h<5> is under a screw h<2>, h<4>, so the stitch cam is intermittently depressed to draw long loops round a portion of the fabric tube, or is pushed up by a spring to draw correspondingly short loops. The splicing-mechanism is pivotally suspended at b<4> from a bracket-piece, and is intermittently operated, when released by the inward movement of the upper end of the bell-crank f, by means of a rotary cam b<1> against which a bearing-surface b<2> is held by a spring. The chain-wheel is operated by a ratchet-wheel p<1> and a pawl p constantly reciprocated by a lever q and cam. The speed of the wheel p<1> can be reduced by means of a cam p<3> pivoted at p<2> and actuated by a lever o<2> and projections on the pattern chain ; when the cam p<3> is moved to the position shown in full lines in Fig. 5, it acts as a bluff and the pawl p drives the wheel p<1> only one tooth at each reciprocation instead of two. The lever q may be held out of range of its cam by a latch q engaging the catch q<2>.

column12: WHEEL HUB WITH INTEGRATED CIRCULAR BRAKE ELEMENT
column13: In one aspect, a wheel hub apparatus including a wheel hub that is rotatable about a central axis and has a unitary, one-piece construction. The wheel hub apparatus further includes a circular brake element having a unitary, one-piece construction and extending about the wheel hub. The wheel hub and the circular brake element include engaged portions securing the wheel hub and the circular brake element together. column12: Improved Brake, Coasting and Driving Gear for Cycles.
column13: 9863. Allan, J., and Moore, F. April 29. Driving-mechanism; clutches; brakes.-Relates to free-wheel driving- mechanism, and back-pedalling and like brakes for bicycles, tricycles, &c. The chain or gear wheel m is carried by a sleeve H, K running on ball bearings n, n<1> and surrounding a collar F fixed to the hub and a collar J screwed on a block B forming part of the bearing-cone b. The sleeve is formed with two circles of inclined holes p, r arranged in opposite directions and corresponding with recesses g, h in the collars F, J respectively. Balls s, as shown by the cross-section, Fig. 3, are placed in the grooves to form clutches. When driven in the direction shown in Fig. 3, the gear-wheel m locks on the collar F and actuates the hub. If the pedals are held stationary, the hub runs free. Back-pedalling brings the second ring of balls into action, and rotates the collar G, which, moving on the screw on the block B, is forced against the collar F and acts as a brake. In a modification, the brake is arranged on the opposite end of the axle A, and is independent of the driving-gear, the collar G being rotated by a cord &c. The axle A is fitted with ball bearings as shown.

column13: A framing jig is provided to insure accurate., consistent hoop framing of garments such as t-shirts, jackets, pants or other items for subsequent embroidering. In addition, an adjustable collar slide permits the easy centering of the garment on the jig.

column12: Hoop press with pivoting platens and method
column13: An embroidery hoop press and method of operation permit the user to frame large areas of thick fabric between inner and outer embroidery hoops by the use of relatively little pressure. column12: Fabric holder with complimentary clamping surfaces and method
column13: A fabric holder and method for maintaining fabric or other flexible planar members in a taut manner for sewing, stitching or embroidering thereon. The fabric is stretched across a portal frame in which the frame sides each have a base with an upward wave-like crest projection. A clamp receptacle receives the projection and fabric thereon to maintain the fabric sandwiched tightly in place. As stresses are applied to the fabric during sewing, the clamp exhibits the ability to rotate outwardly thereby applying a greater gripping force to the fabric to maintain it in place on the frame. After the sewing operation is completed, the clamps can be easily removed for fabric replacement by manually rotating them inwardly, toward the center of the fabric and thereafter lifting the clamp and fabric from the projection.

column13: 11,516. Moore, F., and Palmer, J. May 27. Circular knitting- machines.-To produce embroidery over plain fabric during the course of manufacture, a set of kneed feeders a<4> arranged radially in a dial are directed alternately into and .out of action by an cut-throw cam controlled by a starwheel b<1>. -To traverse the embroidery threads over the fabric, the feeder dial is shogged at intervals by means of pattern-wheels carried below the bed. The dial can be shogged either during the courses in which the feeders are projected, or in the succeeding courses while the feeders are retracted. In the first case, the embroidery threads traverse over the front of the needles and are knitted in. In the second case, the threads traverse behind the needles and float on the reverse side of the fabric. Patternwheels d, d' for ordinary embroidery and the bracelet respectively, are used. To commence the bracelet, the machine is first stopped and a sleeve carrying the wheels d, d' is moved by hand to bring the wheel d<1> against a lever c<2>, the forked upper end of which is connected to the feeder dial. On completion of the bracelet, a cam on the wheel d acting on a fixed incline displaces the sleeve, bringing the wheel d against the lever c<2>. Provision is made for holding the dial and the lever c<2> in the position in which they are placed by the pattern-wheels. For making more complicated embroidery patterns, a multi-part dial with relative movement between the parts can be used.

column13: 648,408. Prepayment gas meters. GLOVER & CO., Ltd., G. Feb. 3, 1948, Nos. 3093 and 6281. [Class 27] [Also in Group XXIX] A prepayment gas meter has a pair of outlets, one e of which is controlled by the auto-valve j, whilst the other f is in permanent communication with the metering mechanism. This second outlet f is for connection to refrigerators or similar apparatus which require an uninterrupted but small supply, and delivery through it is restricted by a small opening k. The quantity mechanism comprises a screw and nut m, n arranged to traverse a slide p in opposite directions during prepayment and consumption. The mechanism is shown in credit, a pin q on the slide holding a spring-loaded lever r connected to the valve j in a position to hold the valve open. When credit is exhausted, the pin q passes a step in the lever r allowing it to rock under the action of its spring s to close the valve. The pin q then moves slowly across the right-hand half of the lever r, as gas is delivered through the outlet f. When a further prepayment is made the pin q must be returned beyond the step in the lever r before the valve j is opened to restore the main supply through the outlet e. In this way payment is secured for all gas delivered through the outlet f. In the modified mechanism of Fig. 2, (not shown), the nut n is connected to the valve j by way of a slidable rod, a compression spring between the nut and rod yielding during restricted consumption through the outlet f after the valve has closed.

column12: ELECTRICAL FILTER COMPRISING AN ACOUSTIC SURFACE WAVE DEVICE, AND METHOD OF MANUFACTURING SUCH A FILTER
column13: In order to obtain greater flexibility in the design of a linear-phase electrical filter which is in the form of an acoustic surface wave device comprising a pair of apodized transducers intercoupled by means of a multi-strip coupler, for example to obtain more equal contributions by the two transducers to the gain versus frequency characteristic of the filter, the transducers are designed to be apodized differently but to have mutually complementary non-linear phase characteristics. In order to achieve this, first a transfer characteristic corresponding to the collective contribution to the overall gain versus frequency characteristic of the filter desired of the two transducers, is derived in terms of the z-transform and the roots or the reciprocals of the roots of the resulting polynomial in z ' are found. These roots or reciprocals are then divided into two groups in such manner that at least one pair of non-identical roots or reciprocals which have equal ratios between their real and imaginary parts and the product of the moduli of which is equal to unity are included one in each group. Two further polynomials are then found which have as their roots or the reciprocals of their roots those of the first group and those of the second group respectively, and the two transducers are constructed with successive active electrode pairs the electrodes constituting which have relative weights proportional to the coefficients of the successively increasing powers of the variable in one further polynomial and the variable in the other further polynomial respectively. The active electrode pairs are connected with polarities which accord with the signs of the corresponding coefficients.

Each heat transfer wall comprises a lower vertically extending portion and an upper outwardly curved portion shaped to cause wastes to flow to the bottom of the frypot. A plurality of burners are provided for maintaining combustion in zones adjacent to the vertically extending portions of the heat transfer walls. This causes heated products of combustion to flow upwardly along the vertically extending and outwardly extending portions of the heat transfer walls, whereby heat transfer is effected through the walls to cooking oil in the frypot. Each burner comprises two or more orifices for discharging mutually interacting gas jets and a target for deflecting the gas jets and entrained air toward the heat transfer walls and for reflecting heat into the combustion zone and through the heat transfer walls. Baffles are provided for preventing recycling of the products of combustion into the combustion zone and for maintaining the cooking oil in the bottom of the frypot relatively cool.

column12: Positive reset safety control system for frying apparatus
column13: Frying apparatus including a fry pot and a filter system operable during a cleaning cycle for dislodging food particles which cling to the fry pot and for removing food particles suspended in the cooking oil is disclosed. The filter system includes a shower apparatus which discharges jets of cooking oil along the interior side surfaces of the fry pot to dislodge food particles clinging thereto. The cooking oil is drained into a drain pan, strained through a filter and means are provided for pumping the filtered cooking oil back to the fry pot where it is discharged through the shower apparatus. Food particles are continuously separated from the cooking oil as it is conveyed from the fry pot through the filter into the drain pot. In a preferred embodiment, a control circuit is provided for automatically turning off the fry pot heaters when the cooking oil is drained during the filter cycle. The control circuit includes means for locking the fry pot heating system in the off condition when the draining operation occurs. Reset is accomplished by first turning the fry pot off and then back on to insure that the operator exercises positive control before the heating system is energized.

column13: A thermostatically controlled safety heater for upright immersion in an aquarium includes a housing with an axially extending, heat-transmitting tube forming a chamber in which an electric heating element is disposed in radially spaced relation from the tube. The radial space between the tube and element, over substantially the axial length of the element, is filled with a heat conducting, thermally expansible liquid. An actuator device including a linearly movable plunger reactive to thermal expansion of the liquid is provided for opening and closing a switch in circuit with the heating element for maintaining the heater at a desired temperature. A hunting tendency of the switch contacts is overcome by providing a damping medium in the form of an air space having a volume less than about ten per cent of the volume of liquid between the plunger and the liquid. An expansible sealing diaphragm supports the plunger and isolates the liquid to the portion of the tube in which the heating element is disposed.

column13: 10,279. Moore, W. E., and Clark, F. R. May 17. Loom shuttles, changing bobbins in, automatically; shuttles; bobbins, pirns, etc.; breast beams; lays; weft forks.-Relates to means for automatically supplying bobbins to shuttles when the weft is practically exhausted, or broken. The bobbins in the magazine shown in Fig. 1, are held between retainers or spring plates e, e<4>, Fig. 4, respectively secured to the endless carriers E, E', which travel upon sprocket-wheels D, D<1>. Each plate e<4> is formed with a bent extension e<6> for holding the thread end. The spindle of the wheels D' is driven intermittently by a pawl and ratchet mechanism actuated by means of an electromagnet G. The bobbin in use is held in a self-threading shuttle H, by spring plates h having transverse grooves which engage with circumferential ribs i<1> on the bobbin. The metallic head I of the bobbin is in electrical connection with a contact-plate h<3>, secured to the shuttle, and this plate h<3> contacts, at the end of every pick, with one or other of two pairs of contactsprings j, j<1> and j<2>, j<3>, secured to the iron raceway of the lay B. The spring j<2> is electrically connected to a battery K, or other source of electricity, and the spring j<3> is connected to an insulated contact-spring L on the breast beam M. The spring L makes contact, at certain times, with a contact-piece L' carried by a shaft N ; the piece L' is electrically connected with the magnet G, which in turn is connected with the battery K. A second electric circuit includes the battery K, magnet G, and two pairs of contact-springs 0, O<1> and P, P'; the circuit is closed through the springs O, O<1> and P, P', respectively, by means of the bobbin retainers e, and a boss Q, secured to a shaft Q<1>. When the shuttle enters the shuttle box C', Fig. 4, the weft thread, if the bobbin is not nearly exhausted, holds up a feeler R, attached to the loom frame ; but if the bobbin is nearly exhausted, the feeler springs into contact with the metallic head of the bobbin, and electrical connection with the battery K is established through the spring j<1>. The feeler is electrically connected to an electromagnet R', which is connected to the battery K, and secured to the weft-slide fork r. The weft-fork hammer S, Fig. 5, forms part of a pivoted lever S<1>, which is oscillated by means of a cam T on the shaft Q'. An arm r<4> of a bell-crank lever r<2>, pivoted to the slide r, forms the armature of the magnet R', and the other arm r<5> engages with the end of the hammer S when the magnet R<1> is excited. An eye r<6>, on the slide r, engages with an arm n secured to the shaft N. When the weft is nearly exhausted, the electric circuit including the magnet R' is closed when the shuttle enters the box C', and the magnet R<1> attracts its armature and causes the arm r<5> to swing across the path of the hammer S, which next actuates the slide r and arm n, causing contact to be made between the pieces L, L'. By these means, the circuit including the magnet G is partially closed, and, when the shuttle enters the shuttle box C, the spring h<3> completes the circuit across the springs j<2>, j<3>, and the magnet G is caused to actuate the bobbin magazine, so that a full bobbin is brought into the position indicated at 2, Fig. 1. The lay then beats-up, and forces the shuttle into engagement with the full bobbin, while the empty bobbin is ejected. The empty bobbin retainers are then moved into the position 3 by the action of the magnet G, which is again excited by a current in a circuit closed by means of the springs O, O<1> and P, P<1>. When the weft thread breaks, the weft fork falls across the path of the hammer S, and the circuit including the magnet G is partly completed by contact between the pieces L, L', and this circuit is completed when the shuttle reaches the box C. The ensuing action is the same as that described as taking place.when the weft is nearly exhausted. Cases containing bobbins may be placed in the magazine, and may be transferred to the shuttle in the same way as when bobbins alone are employed.

In Fig. 3 (not shown), a spring plate is fitted to extend slightly within bore 13, Fig. 1, for tighter engagement with the shaft.

column12: Spray cleaning system for frying apparatus
column13: Frying apparatus including a fry pot and a filter system operable during a cleaning cycle for dislodging food particles which cling to the fry pot and for removing food particles suspended in the cooking oil is disclosed. The filter system includes a shower apparatus which discharges jets of cooking oil along the interior side surfaces of the fry pot to dislodge food particles clinging thereto. The cooking oil is drained into a drain pan, strained through a filter and means are provided for pumping the filtered cooking oil back to the fry pot where it is discharged through the shower apparatus. Food particles are continuously separated from the cooking oil as it is conveyed from the fry pot through the filter into the drain pot. In a preferred embodiment, a control circuit is provided for automatically turning off the fry pot heaters when the cooking oil is drained during the filter cycle. The control circuit includes means for locking the fry pot heating system in the off condition when the draining operation occurs. Reset is accomplished by first turning the fry pot off and then back on to insure that the operator exercises positive control before the heating system is energized.

column13: Compositions and methods useful for the removal of organic substances from substrates, for example, electronic device substrates, are provided. column12: METHOD AND DEVICE FOR STICKING PLASTIC LABEL AROUND VESSEL
column13: In this method and this appliance, the containers C to be subjected to pasteurisation temperatures are labelled with plastic labels 41 which are wound around the body of the container. The labels are made from a preglued material which may be in the form of a continuous strip or in the form of individual labels. The adhesive or glue is a polymer activated by heat, in an aqueous medium, which crosslinks under the effect of the heat. The containers and the labels are transported as far as a position where the front edge of the label comes into contact with the glue present on the label. The container is preheated, or the glue is heated so as to adhere to the container. The container is made to roll over the label so as to roll the label around the container and the overlapping end of the label also has glue activated by heat which comes either from the container, or from hot air blown on the glue before it welds itself against the front edge of the label. In this manner, an encircling label made from thin plastic may be glued to a container containing a product which is to be pasteurised.

column12: Scrambling of data streams having arbitrary data path widths
column13: An arrangement is described for scrambling data streams having arbitrary data path widths. The arrangement includes logic configured to generate a maximal length pseudorandom sequence of digital signals. A first register is configured to store the pseudorandom sequence. Logic, coupled to the first register, is configured to combine a portion of the pseudorandom sequence with a corresponding portion of an input data stream to produce a scrambled data word. A second register is configured to store the scrambled data word. Circuitry is configured to circularly shift the pseudorandom sequence a number of bits forming the portion of the pseudorandom sequence used to produce the scrambled data word.

column12: Electrical filter comprising an acoustic surface wave device, and method of manufacturing such a filter.
column13: In order to obtain greater flexibility in the design of a linear-phase electrical filter which is in the form of an acoustic surface wave device comprising a pair of apodized transducers intercoupled by means of a multi-strip coupler, for example to obtain more equal contributions by the two transducers to the gain versus frequency characteristic of the filter, the transducers are designed to be apodized differently but to have mutually complementary non-linear phase characteristics. In order to achieve this, first a transfer characteristic corresponding to the collective contribution to the overall gain versus frequency characteristic of the filter desired of the two transducers, is derived in terms of the z-transform and the roots or the reciprocals of the roots of the resulting polynomial in z ' are found. These roots or reciprocals are then divided into two groups in such manner that at least one pair of non-identical roots or reciprocals which have equal ratios between their real and imaginary parts and the product of the moduli of which is equal to unity are included one in each group. Two further polynomials are then found which have as their roots or the reciprocals of their roots those of the first group and those of the second group respectively, and the two transducers are constructed with successive active electrode pairs the electrodes constituting which have relative weights proportional to the coefficients of the successively increasing powers of the variable in one further polynomial and the variable in the other further polynomial respectively. The active electrode pairs are connected with polarities which accord with the signs of the corresponding coefficients.

column12: A New or Improved Method of and Means for Storing Gases.
column13: 117,842. Short, F. C., and Moore, F. W. July 31, 1917. Gases, solid absorbents for. - Gases, such as coal gas for internal-combustion engines, lighting, heating, &c., are absorbed for storage in receptacles, such as cylinders, by charcoal preferably of coco.nut shell, impregnated with a metal possessing higher absorptive power for the gases than charcoal; the charcoal may be broken or powdered, the metal may be platinum, gold, pal. ladium, iron, nickel, or cobalt, and the charcoal may be impregnated with a salt of the metal and the salt reduced by heat or a suitable reducing- agent. Thus coco-nut shell charcoal may be impregnated with ferric chloride and the salt reduced to the condition of finely divided metallic iron by a reducing-agent such as coal gas. column12: Armor steel products and method for making same
column13: A process for making steel armor products for use, for example as body armor. The steel armor product made has a compound curve and is made from a flat blank of armor steel by high-temperature annealing an armor steel blank to slightly above its austenitizing temperature, then followed by a slow, temperature-controlled cooling it, over-pressing the annealed blank to a first configuration so it springs back to a second configuration approximating the desired product shape when released from the press, and then heat-treating the product back to its austenitizing temperature, quenching it, and tempering it at a low temperature. The tool is conveniently made by lamination, using a series of thin plates of tool steel each cut to produce an approximation of the desired die.

column13: 7037. Lelson, J. M. K., and Burpee, F. W. March 22. Soldering.-Relates to a machine for soldering the tops and bottoms on cans, the machine being of the class in which the cans are rolled in a continuous succession along a trough of molten solder in which their lower edges are immersed. Fig. 1 shows in elevation the ends of the machine, Fig 3, a cross-section of the solder trough with a can rolling therethrough, and Fig. 10 a perspective view of the turnover guide at the leaving-end of the machine. The cans rolling from the crimper at 20<b> are engaged successively by fingers 45 of the chain 12 which runs the whole length of the machine above and below it. The groove 4<c> is provided along which the chain may run. In order that the lower edges of the cans may roll in the trough at the required angle, the bar 6 is carried in a support 7 which is adjustable vertically and at right-angles to the machine by eccentrics and levers. The edges of the cans are first rolled through an acid bath, drops being allowed to drain away. By means of a screw arrangement, the level of the fluxing-groove may be maintained, the flux being supplied by an inverted vessel. The cans are then taken by the fingers of the chain to the soldering-trough 2 arranged above a furnace. On leaving the trough, the cans enter the turnover guide-way 54, drop their surplus solder, and disengage themselves from the fingers with their bottom ends on the conveyer-band 55 by which they are removed from the machine. The piece 4 extends the whole length of the trough and is supported and aligned at intermediate points by set-screws. To allow the lower edge of the plate to expand freely, the angled portion of it is divided into sections. The standards 15, which at each end of the machine sustain the operating mechanism, support adjustable sleeves upon which the pulleys for operating the chain are supported, the chain passing round the pulleys as indicated in dotted lines. As regards the chain-fingers each has two ridges so that a finger rubs a can at two points only. The entering roll-way of the machine is formed with raised side-walls to prevent a can from being thrown out if it overrides a finger. The back portion 54<a>, Fig. 10, which slopes downwardly, is of wood. The bearings of the spindle of the driving-pulley are made adjustable.

column12: Metal-safe solid form aqueous-based compositions and methods to remove polymeric materials in electronics manufacturing
column13: Compositions and methods useful for the removal of organic substances from substrates, for example, electronic device substrates, are provided. These compositions and methods are particularly suitable for removing and completely dissolving photoresists of the positive variety most commonly used in the manufacture of a flat panel display (FPD) and other electronic substrates.

column12: Using a dither signal to minimize data-dependent power variations in a device
column13: A system minimises data-dependent power fluctuations in a mixed-signal device, such as an ADC or DAC. The system includes summing an input signal 101 with a dither signal 202 produced by dither generator 201. Processing means 100, e.g. an interpolator or decimator, processes the summed signal 203. The effects of dither are substantially removed from output 204 by equivalently processing the dither signal 202 alone using duplicate or equivalent processing means 200. The processed dither signal 206 is subtracted from output 204 using summer 208, thereby cancelling components of the processed signal that result from the presence of the dither signal. Randomizing the input signal by summing it with dither signal 202 ensures that the power consumption of the device is essentially constant regardless of fluctuations in input signal. Unwanted variations in operating temperature in an ASIC are avoided. Non-linear operation of units 100, 200 is avoided by two's complement arithmetic or by constraining the amplitude of the dither signal with scalers (311, 312).

column13: LIQUID DISTRIBUTOR A liquid distributor for liquid/gas contact apparatus has a liquid feed splitter dividing the liquid supplied thereto at a specific rate of flow into a plurality of streams, and an array of troughs extending across the cross sectional area of the contact apparatus, below the splitter, collects the liquid streams and divides the liquid flowing from the troughs into a greater number of liquid streams. A shallow pan situated under each of the troughs collects the liquid streams flowing from the troughs and has upturned sides with drain openings therein, of greater number than the liquid streams deposited in the pan, extending upwardly from at least the junction with a downwardly sloping bottom of the pan over which the liquid spreads and flows toward the junction and is again divided into a still greater number of smaller streams as it passes through the drain openings and thereby more uniformly distributed onto a bed of tower packing for contact with a gas flowing therethrough. Thus, the drain openings extending upwardly from the junction allow the liquid supplied at relatively low rates of flow to pass in relatively thin streams substantially without interference or increasing the level of the liquid in the pans.

column12: Improvements in or relating to electrically-maintained balances for use in timing devices
column13: 906,998. Clocks and watches. SMITH & SONS (ENGLAND) Ltd., S. Jan. 8, 1959 [Jan. 8, 1958], No. 817/58. Class 139. In an electric timepiece a coil 3, Fig. 1, carried by the balance staff 2, oscillates in the gap between a soft iron member 13 and the polepieces 11, 12 of a permanent magnet 10. The maintaining circuit, Fig. 2, includes a transformer 24, a transistor 21, a rectifier 23 and a voltage source 20, 22. As the coil swings through the magnetic field a voltage is induced in it to cause a current to flow in the primary winding of transformer 24. When the base of the transistor is driven negative, as the balance swings in one direction, a collector current flows through coil 3 in opposition to the induced voltage and a maintaining impulse is imparted to the balance. The induced secondary transformer voltage drops to zero when the transformer core reaches saturation and the transistor returns to its quiescent condition. The balance springs 5, 6 are connected to the coil 3 by wires 16, 17, respectively. The circuit is such as to tend to keep the amplitude of balance oscillation constant. The coil may be of rectangular form, Fig. 3 (not shown), and supported from the periphery of the balance to co-operate with a short bar magnet secured between the limbs of a V-shaped soft iron member. Specifications 227,499 and 300,992 are referred to.

column12: Dither methods for suppression of data-dependent activity variations
column13: A system and method are provided for minimizing data-dependent power variations. The system and method can include summing an input with a dither signal, processing the summed signal, and substantially removing the effects of the dither signal from the output. The output is an approximation of processing to the input alone, while certain aspects of processing activity, such as temperature changes and current draw, are less dependent on input values. Variations in data-dependent activities are thus reduced. The effects of the dither signal may be removed by equivalently processing the dither signal alone, and using that result as a compensating signal to cancel components of the processed signal that result from the presence of the dither signal.

column13: A belt for restraining an occupant in a vehicle includes a first and second layers extending from a first end of the belt to a second end of the belt, and a seal joining the first and second layers to form an inflatable portion of the belt. column12: METHOD AND SYSTEM FOR MITIGATING RISK IN ISSUING WIND ONLY INSURANCE
column13:
PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To mitigate the risk of issuing insurance by greatly reducing the risk of uplifting deck and walls or the like by high wind by using a building system with a wind uplift resistant foam adhered thereto.

SOLUTION: When a request for the wind only insurance is submitted, if a building complies with a predetermined set of parameters is determined. If the building complies with a predetermined set of parameters, the request for the wind only insurance is admitted to issue the wind only insurance. If the building does not comply, a site visit is arranged to make improvement so as to allow the building to comply. Consequently, this reduces the risk for issuing the wind only insurance.

column12: FOLDING PATTERNS OF INFLATABLE SEAT BELT
column13: To provide an inflatable seat belt adopting folding patterns for improving the amount of power that can be absorbed.SOLUTION: An inflatable portion 14 includes a first wing portion 32a, a second wing portion 32b, a central region forming an outer shell 30, and a breakable seam portion, and they are disposed within the inflatable portion. The first wing portion has first width and the second wing portion has second width that is different from the first width. The breakable seam portion separates the inside of the inflatable portion from the inside of the first wing portion and the inside of the second wing portion. The breakable seam portion is configured to break when the belt is inflated, allowing gas to fill the first wing portion and the second wing portion and expand the first wing portion and the second wing portion laterally outward. The first wing portion and the second wing portion are arranged so that they are overlapped with the outside of the outer shell. By inverting the inflatable portion so that the first wing portion and the second wing portion are positioned within the outer shell, the belt becomes in a housing state.SELECTED DRAWING: Figure 1

column12: System and method for selecting Doppler altered reflected signals
column13: A matched transmission line coupling an RF generator to an antenna and receiving Doppler altered reflected signals from the antenna. A pair of diodes coupled to the transmission line 90 electrical degrees apart at the RF frequency and oppositely poled so that the RF signal from the generator and the reflected signal from the antenna are heterodyned in each diode to produce a heterodyne signal which is in phase. The heterodyne signals are band limited, filtered and passed through threshold detectors separately to provide separate in phase pulses which are applied to a coincidence gate to provide an output. Amplitude modulation is rejected because it produces out of phase signals and frequency modulation is rejected because the transmission line is substantially flat. The RF generator may be frequency modulated and the output of the coincidence gate is applied to a shift register to insure the triggering thereof by only a true Doppler signal.

column12: METHOD AND SYSTEM FOR MITIGATING RISK IN ISSUING INSURANCE
column13:
PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To mitigate risk of issuing insurance.

SOLUTION: When a claim for the insurance is presented, it is decided whether a method, material, system or item complies with a predetermined set of parameters or not, the insurance is issued when it complies, and a visit to a site is arranged when not complying. The parameter is selected from a group comprising a foam heat insulation material, shock resistance, cut resistance, energy management, alert sensors, process control, weather resistance, water resistance, mold resistance, loss of business, loss of property, loss to the environment, avionics, injury to persons, and security.

column13: Ein Gurt zum Zurückhalten eines Insassen in einem Fahrzeug weist eine erste und eine zweite Lage, welche sich von einem ersten Ende des Gurtes zu einem zweiten Ende des Gurtes erstrecken, und eine die beiden Lagen verbindende Abdichtung, um ein abgedichtetes Inneres des Gurtes zu bilden, auf. Der aufblasbare Teil beinhaltet einen ersten Flügel, einen zweiten Flügel und eine Reißnaht. Der erste und der zweite Flügel sind innerhalb des aufblasbaren Teils angeordnet. Der erste Flügel hat eine erste Breite und der zweite Flügel hat eine zweite Breite, welche in einem Beispiel von der ersten Breite verschieden ist. Die Reißnaht trennt das Innere des aufblasbaren Teils von den Inneren der ersten und zweiten Flügel. Die Reißnaht ist so ausgebildet, dass sie reißt, wenn der Gurt aufgeblasen wird, wodurch es unter Druck stehendem Gas ermöglicht wird, die ersten und zweiten Flügel zu füllen und die ersten und zweiten Flügel nach außen auszudehnen.

column12: Lateral bipolar junction transistor with reduced parasitic current loss
column13: A semiconductor process is disclosed which forms openings in a dielectric layer through which the emitter region and collector region of lateral bipolar junction transistors are formed. In one embodiment of the invention, the emitter openings for the lateral bipolar junction transistors are first protected by a photoresist layer that is patterned to expose the collector openings for the transistors. A first implant is performed through the exposed windows in the dielectric layer and into the exposed substrate or epitaxial layer therebelow, and then diffused to a suitable depth. The patterned photoresist is then removed to additionally expose the emitter openings, and a second implant is performed, this time into both the collector and the emitter regions, and then diffused to a suitable depth that is shallower than the first implant (used in the collector). Since the two implants are aligned to openings through the dielectric layer defined typically by a single mask, excellent base-width control and repeatability is achieved for the lateral transistors. Through careful selection of the collector and emitter diffusion profiles (i.e., depth and concentration), a more optimal PNP transistor may be constructed that has a collector deeper than its emitter. This scheme provides far greater collection efficiency than a traditional lateral PNP transistor made of the same diffusion for both the emitter and the collector. Greater collection efficiency provides improved Beta, better gain matching, and less parasitic loss of injected holes to a surrounding P-type junction isolation.

column12: FOLDING PATTERNS OF AN INFLATABLE SEAT BELT
column13: A belt for restraining an occupant in a vehicle includes a first and second layers extending from a first end of the belt to a second end of the belt, and a seal joining the first and second layers to form an inflatable portion of the belt. The inflatable portion includes a first wing, a second wing, and a tear seam. The first and second wings are disposed within the inflatable portion. The first wing has a first width and the second wing has a second width that, in one example, is different than the first width. The tear seam separates the interior of the inflatable portion from the interiors of the first and second wings. The tear seam is configured to tear when the belt is inflated, allowing gas to fill the first and second wings and expand the first and second wings laterally outward.

column12: INTEGRATED ROOF WIND RISK MITIGATION METHOD AND SYSTEM
column13:
PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To drastically mitigate risk wherein a roof is uplifted by a strong wind by use of a specific roofing system wherein window uplift resistant foam is bonded, to mitigate risk of issuing insurance.

SOLUTION: When a claim for the wind only roof insurance is presented, it is decided whether the roofing system complies with a predetermined set of parameters or not, the claim for the wind only roof insurance is permitted when the roofing system complies, and the wind only roof insurance is issued. When not complying, a facility site visit is arranged, and compliance is improved. Thereby, the risk of issuing the wind only roof insurance is mitigated.

column13: A ring oscillator comprises CMOS inverters 11-15 linked by sensing resistors 40-44 so that the frequency of oscillation varies in dependence on the stimulus applied to the resistors. The resistors may be polycrystalline piezoresistive elements located on a cantilever 220 to sense acceleration. Alternatively they may sense pressure or strain or gas. The inverters 11 - 15 are supported on the substrate so that they are not subject to the applied stimulus, and there may be a matched reference ring oscillator in which the resistors are not subject to the stimulus. One of the interconnecting resistors may have a greater resistance than that of the others so that a change in its resistance dominates the output frequency. Fingerprint sensing is disclosed.

column12: Bipolar junction transistor incorporating integral field plate
column13: A semiconductor process is disclosed which forms a field plate structure that integrally contacts an emitter region of a bipolar junction transistor by construction, without intervening interconnect layers or contacts. In one embodiment, a single-layer polysilicon electrode forms a field plate electrode which integrally interconnects to a traditional diffused emitter region formed before the polysilicon layer is deposited. This allows for deeper emitter regions required by the deep base regions needed for high-voltage bipolar devices. Moreover, the polysilicon layer, including the polysilicon electrode forming the field plate electrode, may be used as a local interconnect layer.

column12: POSTIVE-WORKING PHOTOSENSITIVE POLYMIDE OPERATED BY PHOTO INDUCED MOLECULAR WEIGHT CHANGES
column13:
An insoluble photosensitive polyimide having the formula
   can be exposed by a pattern of light to render the exposed areas soluble. The exposed areas can then be dissolved using a solvent to leave the pattern which can be used directly as an insulator layer in a semiconductor device. A process for preparing the photosensitive soluble polyimide utilizes maleic anhydride which is irradiated by ultraviolet light to form a cyclobutane unit which is reacted with oxydianiline to form polyamic acid. The polyamic acid is cured using heat into the photosensitive soluble polyimide.

column13: A micromechanical sensor has a plurality of sensing elements (14a - 14d) which are supported at respective support regions (12a - 12d). A first set of the sensing elements defines the sensing gap. In one arrangement this is defined by sensing elements supported by adjacent support regions. In another embodiment the sensing gap is defined between one sensing element and a reference beam formed by connection of the return legs of two diametrically opposed sensing elements. The sensing elements are substantially similar one to another and each sensing element comprises an outgoing elongate leg extending away from its associated support region and a return leg substantially parallel to the outgoing leg extending towards the support region. By providing sensing elements which are substantially similar in shape and arranged in this way, the effects of thin film stress are minimised. <IMAGE>

column12: Self-aligned dual-base semiconductor process and structure incorporating multiple bipolar device types
column13: A semiconductor process is disclosed which forms openings in a dielectric layer through which the base region of both high-voltage and high-gain bipolar transistors are formed. In one embodiment of the invention, the openings for the high-gain transistors are first protected by a photoresist layer that is patterned to expose the openings for the high-voltage transistors. A first base implant is performed through the exposed windows in the dielectric layer and into the exposed substrate or epitaxial layer therebelow, and then diffused to a suitable depth. The patterned photoresist is then removed to additionally expose the openings for the high-gain devices, and a second base implant is performed, this time into both base regions, and then diffused to a suitable depth. Emitter regions are then formed within the base regions of both transistor types by traditional implantation and contact techniques. Since the two base implants for each high-voltage transistor are self-aligned to a single opening through the dielectric layer, excellent control and repeatability is achieved for the high-voltage transistors. Moreover, since the second base implant is common to both types of transistors, many of the characteristics of the two types of transistors are well matched to each other.

column12: Arrangement for the generation of sonic fields of a specific modal composition
column13: A device for simulating sound produced by certain equipment, for example a rotor-stator arrangement of a turbomachine, or for generation of opposing sound fields for active sound control, including active sound reduction and active sound amplification, comprises flow obstacles ( 2 ) provided in a flow duct ( 1 ) flown by a fluid at which vortices ( 5, 6 ) are shed at a certain frequency depending on the shape and size of the flow obstacles and the velocity of flow. The quantity and spatial arrangement of the flow obstacles is selected such that a periodically spatially and temporally changing pressure field for the excitation of a sound field ( 8 ) of a certain modal content is produced by the entirety of the vortices shed. This sound field reacts synchronizingly on the vortex shedding. The resonant circuit so formed, whose vortex shedding frequency is in the range of the resonant frequency of the sound field to be excited, is the sound source.

column12: CLEANING STRUCTURE AND METHOD FOR FRICTION ROLL FEEDERS
column13: With a cleaning system/method, a user places a printing device in a cleaning mode, inserts a cleaning apparatus that includes a cleaning sheet into a paper supply tray of the printing device, and executes a cleaning operation on the printing device. With the system, a set of instructions is stored on a machine-readable medium. The set of instructions causes the printing device to execute a cleaning operation on a feed nip of the printing device. The cleaning sheet cleans the feed roller and the retard roller when it is positioned within the feed nip during the cleaning operation. The set of instructions cause the printing device to move the cleaning sheet into the feed nip and to rotate the feed roller and the retard roller for a predetermined time period, when the printing device is placed into a cleaning mode.

column12: SHARING SYNDICATED FEED BOOKMARKS AMONG MEMBERS OF A SOCIAL NETWORK
column13: A computer-implemented method of bookmarking syndicated feeds. The method can include receiving a request to bookmark a first network resource and determining whether at least one syndicated feed is associated with the first network resource. When at least one syndicated feed is associated with the first network resource, the syndicated feed can be identified to a user and the user can be prompted to indicate whether to bookmark the syndicated feed. Responsive to receiving an indication from the user to bookmark the syndicated feed, a bookmark can be generated for the syndicated feed and the syndicated feed bookmark can be output.

column12: Improvements in or relating to the stabilization of the output voltage of a direct current electric supply system
column13: 899,528. Automatic voltage control systems. PLESSEY CO. Ltd. June 16, 1959 [June 24, 1958], No. 20169/58. Class 38 (4). In an automatic direct-voltage control system, a field of a dynamo in series with a supply is controlled differentially by the output voltage and a stabilized reference voltage. In an embodiment, a generator armature 1, in series with an output terminal 3, is driven by a motor 4 connected across a supply 2. A field 18 of the generator is fed from the supply via a resistor 19a. The output of an alternator 5 driven by the motor 4 feeds a full-wave rectifier 7 through the main windings 21, 22 of a saturable reactor 25. The rectified alternator output through a control winding 16 of the saturable reactor 25, is fed to a voltage regulator tube 26 shunted by Zener diodes 9 in series with a resistor 8. The flux of a second control winding 20, energized from the stabilized voltage, is opposed by the flux from the control winding 16 so as to tend to maintain constant the output voltage of the rectifier 7. A full-wave rectifier 14 is fed from the alternator 5 via windings 12, 13 of a magnetic amplifier 6 and energizes a field 17 of the generator via a feedback control winding 10, the flux of which is additive to that of a bias-winding 15 energized from the stabilized output and adjusted by a variable resistor 23. The flux due to the bias and feedback windings is opposed by the flux of a control winding 11, energized by the difference between the output voltage and the voltage across Zener diodes 9, so as to vary the current in the field 17 of the generator to maintain the output voltage constant. In a modification, the bias-winding 15 is left out and the resistor 8 is directly connected to the rectifier 7 and the generator voltage adjusted by variation of the valve of the resistor 19a.

column12: MICROCONNECTORS AND METHOD FOR THEIR PRODUCTION
column13: A method of producing a female microconnector for connection to a microcomponent having a corresponding male connector, the method comprising the steps of depositing a first layer (31) on a substrate (20), removing a selected portion of the first layer, and removing a selected portion of the substrate to define a recess (22) having a opening in the substrate with one or more portions of the first layer (21) partially extending over the opening of the recess, the material and thickness of the first layer selected such that when a corresponding male connector (11) is inserted into the recess, the one or more portions of the first layer extending over the opening of the recess flex to hold the male connector in the desired position within the recess, wherein the selected portion of the substrate is removed by (i) a first etching process using a first etchant to undercut the first layer, the etch period of the first etching process being selected to etch a first width sufficient to allow the first layer to flex; and (ii) a second etching process using a second etchant different to the first etchant to etch to a second width to undercut the first layer, the etch period of the second etching process being selected so that the second width is less than the first width, wherein the etch rate of the second etching process normal to the plane of the first layer is greater than the etch rate parallel to the plane of the first layer.

column12: Material for attenuating light signals with low reflectance in a fiber optic network
column13: A fiber optic attenuating element is formed of a thermoplastic polymer having (i) a refractive index in the range of between about 1.42 and 1.47 as measured at a temperature of 230 C. and a wavelength of 1550 nm, (ii) a glass transition temperature of at least 105 C., and (iii) an intrinsic loss of less than one dB/mm at 1310 and 1550 nm. In disclosed embodiments, the polymer includes at least one monomer including fluorinated moieties and, optionally, one or more additional monomers. A main body portion of the element has a first planar contact face on a first side and a second planar contact face on a second, opposite side. The contact faces are dimensioned to couple optically with first and second optical fibers when ends of the fibers are urged against the faces by parts of an attenuator device in which the element is mounted.

column13: A micromechanical sensor has a plurality of sensing elements (14a - 14d) which are supported at respective support regions (12a - 12d). A first set of the sensing elements defines the sensing gap. In one arrangement this is defined by sensing elements supported by adjacent support regions. In another embodiment the sensing gap is defined between one sensing element and a reference beam formed by connection of the return legs of two diametrically opposed sensing elements. The sensing elements are substantially similar one to another and each sensing element comprises an outgoing elongate leg extending away from its associated support region and a return leg substantially parallel to the outgoing leg extending towards the support region. By providing sensing elements which are substantially similar in shape and arranged in this way, the effects of thin film stress are minimised. <IMAGE>

column13: A transfer system for dispensing controlled amounts of liquid. The system including a plurality of reservoirs, each having at least one nozzle commonly provided on a lower side of the reservoir, a plurality of momentum transfer components, each of which is supported for vertical movement in a respective one of the plurality of reservoirs from a rest position in which a lower surface of the transfer component is located within the respective reservoir facing the nozzle, and an actuator provided externally of the reservoir for accelerating the transfer components downwardly relative to the reservoir. The system may simultaneously fill a selected number or all of an array of vessels or to produce a microarray on a substrate surface. A method includes accelerating a transfer component supported in a reservoir from a rest position towards the nozzle and reducing the distance of the component from the nozzle in the rest position.

column12: Postive-working photosensitive polymide operated by photo induced molecular weight changes.
column13:
An insoluble photosensitive polyimide having the formula
   can be exposed by a pattern of light to render the exposed areas soluble. The exposed areas can then be dissolved using a solvent to leave the pattern which can be used directly as an insulator layer in a semiconductor device. A process for preparing the photosensitive soluble polyimide utilizes maleic anhydride which is irradiated by ultraviolet light to form a cyclobutane unit which is reacted with oxydianiline to form polyamic acid. The polyamic acid is cured using heat into the photosensitive soluble polyimide.

column12: DIMENSIONAL DOCUMENT PRODUCTION METHOD AND SYSTEM
column13: A method and system generate a workflow for the production of a three-dimensional document. A knowledge base contains production rules for several dimensional documents. The production rules relate to a plurality of jobs, i.e., units of work involved in the production of a dimensional document. The rules also identify human and/or mechanical resources required to complete each job. The system receives, from multiple service providers, capability information corresponding to each service provider's available resources. The capability information is associated with the production rules and stored in the knowledge base. When a user selects a dimensional document to be produced, the system selects appropriate production rules for the document, accesses the associated capability information, and automatically generates a workflow for the document. The system distributes various jobs in the workflow among at least two different service providers.

A deep fat fryer comprises a vat A and heating elements 47, a removable cover assembly including a pair of lids B and C mounted on hinges 27 for covering the top of the vat A when in a closed position, a pair of baskets supporting members E, a basket D carried on each of said members E and means F for independently raising and lowering the baskets into the vat so that edibles in one basket can be cooked with the lid closed whilst edibles in the other basket can be cooked with the lid open. The cover assembly may include a vertical partition G and have the lids B and C, when closed, arranged in the path of the basket supporting members E so that the lids are opened by the supporting members when they are raised, with the baskets D, out of the vat. The vat A may have a thermostat 58 in series with the electrical heating elements 47 and a trough-like boil-over receptacle carried adjacent the top front edge of the vat. The boil-over receptacle may communicate with the vat for returning boiled over fat to the vat.

column12: METHOD AND APPARATUS FOR IMAGE ANALYSIS
column13: A method and apparatus are described for the analysis of a sample image, e.g. as in blood-typing. The method comprises the steps of presenting the sample image to a single black and white camera, viewing the sample image by said black and white camera sequentially through at least two colour filter means interposed in the optical path between the sample image and the camera; digitising and storing in computer memory means a grey scale picture from the output of said camera after viewing the sample image through each of said at least two colour filter means; analysing by computer program means at least one of said stored digitised camera picture outputs of the sample image to determine positional data of physical shape elements of said sample image; combining said at least two grey scale pictures in said computer memory means by computer program means to form a composite grey scale picture of said sample image; assigning a value to each shade and allocating a specific colour to each of said values in said composite grey scale picture from a range of chosen colours stored in said computer program to generate a colour picture of said sample image.

column13: A micromechanical sensor has a plurality of sensing elements (14a - 14d) which are supported at respective support regions (12a - 12d). A first set of the sensing elements defines the sensing gap. In one arrangement this is defined by sensing elements supported by adjacent support regions. In another embodiment the sensing gap is defined between one sensing element and a reference beam formed by connection of the return legs of two diametrically opposed sensing elements. The sensing elements are substantially similar one to another and each sensing element comprises an outgoing elongate leg extending away from its associated support region and a return leg substantially parallel to the outgoing leg extending towards the support region. By providing sensing elements which are substantially similar in shape and arranged in this way, the effects of thin film stress are minimised. <IMAGE>

Der Deckel (9, 18) weist an seinem freien Rand eine abwärts gerichtete Randleiste (13, 20) auf, welche bei Schliessstellung des Deckels (9, 18) die seitliche Behälteröffnung lichtdicht überdeckt. Die rechteckige öffnung (10) hat eine etwas geringere Flächenausdehnung als die Vertiefung (7, 27), so dass der Deckel (9, 18) eine die Randbereiche eines in die Vertiefung (7, 27) eingelegten Bogens (3, 26) des im Behälter aufbewahrten Materials abdeckende Filmmaske bildet. Der Behälter (1) und Deckel (9, 18) bestehen aus lichtundurchlässigem Material, Insbesondere aus Polystyrol, aus Polypropylen oder aus eine Russbeimischung enthaltendem Akrylnitril-Butadien-Styrolkopolymer.

column13: A phototimer for controlling x-ray exposure includes an array of x-ray sensors, and digital processing electronics for calculating x-ray exposure by selecting one or more signals from the x-ray sensors, and calculating the x-ray exposure from the selected signals. After calculating the x-ray exposure, the calculated exposure is employed to control the x-ray exposure either by displaying the calculated exposure to an operator who compares the calculated exposure with a desired exposure and repeats the exposure if necessary, or by automatically terminating the exposure by sending a control signal to the x-ray source. The improvement in the state of x-ray phototimer technology resides in the automatic selection of a subset of signals from a plurality of photosensors, thereby improving the reliability of the measurement. In prior art devices, the signals from a plurality of sensors were either selected manually by a switch, or all employed in a predetermined algorithm.

column12: Pulsating aneurysm`s tearing risk x-ray based evaluation method, involves correlating extracted aneurysm measured values with clinically established values in order to evaluate tearing risk of aneurysm
column13: The method involves injecting a contrast-improved medium into a patient with an pulsating aneurysm. A sequence of two dimensional (2D) x-rays of the aneurysm is determined over a heart cycle. A linear or range measurement of the aneurysm from the sequence of images is extracted. The extracted aneurysm measured values are correlated with clinically established values in order to evaluate a tearing risk of the aneurysm. Signals for triggering the determination of the image sequence are provided using electrocardiogram. An independent claim is also included for a program memory device comprising a set of instructions for implementing a method for evaluation of a tearing risk of an aneurysm from temporally disintegrated images.

column12: TRACK AND HOLD CIRCUITS FOR HIGH SPEED AND INTERLEAVED ADCS
column13: Improved track and hold (T/H) circuits can help analog-to-digital converters (ADCs) achieve higher performance and lower power consumption. The improved T/H circuits can drive high speed and interleaved ADCs, and the design of the circuits enable additive and multiplicative pseudo-random dither signals to be injected in the T/H circuits. The dither signals can be used to calibrate (e.g., linearize) the T/H circuits and the ADC(s). In addition, the dither signal can be used to dither any remaining non-linearity, and to calibrate offset/gain mismatches in interleaved ADCs. The T/H circuit design also can integrate an amplifier in the T/H circuit, which can be used to improve the signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) of the ADC or to act as a variable gain amplifier (VGA) in front of the ADC.

column12: Device for producing acoustic fields with a defined modal composition
column13: Eine Anordnung zur Simulation des von bestimmten Vorrichtungen, zum Beispiel einer Rotor-Stator-Anordnung einer Turbomaschine, erzeugten Schalls oder auch zur Erzeugung von Gegenschallfeldern für die aktive Schallminderung umfasst in einem von einem fließfähigen Medium durchströmten Strömungskanal (1) ausgebildete Strömungshindernisse (2), von denen in Abhängigkeit von ihrer Form und Größe und der Strömungsgeschwindigkeit in einer bestimmten Frequenz Wirbel (5, 6) abgelöst werden. Dieses Schallfeld wirkt synchronisierend auf die Wirbelbildung zurück. column13: An extruder die head for producing multilayered tubes made of thermoplastic material exhibits a central annular channel, which is provided with an annular outlet die. Into the outer limiting wall of the channel empty annular slits, which feed a polymer melt and which constitute the smaller diameter openings of truncated channels, formed between the internal and external shells of stacked, conical insert members. column13: A solution for managing a set of collaborative contacts is provided. Each collaborative contact includes one or more collaboration capabilities, each of which corresponds to a unique collaboration tool (e.g., voice over IP, instant messaging, email, and/or the like). Identifying text can be used to search the set of collaborative contacts and obtain a set of candidate contacts. An availability status for each collaboration capability of each candidate contact can be requested and a display can be generated that includes the set of candidate contacts. In one embodiment, the display can include an indication of the collaboration capabilities for one or more of the candidate contacts, and/or the availability status for one or more collaboration capabilities. A user can use the display to request a collaboration session between the user and one or more of the candidate contacts.
