column12: Method and system for synchronizing mobile devices
column13: A protocol for synchronizing data is provided. Additionally, a system and method of using the protocol are also provided. The protocol allows responses to be grouped with commands in a single XML document. It provides a command for requesting a single object be sent without requiring that all unsynchronized objects be sent. It provides a command for specifying how many objects at a time should be sent and a response that indicates that more objects are available to be sent. It provides a means for arbitrarily extending the protocol in application-specific ways. It provides a means for sending updates while requesting that no updates be sent back.

column12: Transfer caller into speech make-a-payment transaction
column13: A user calling a payment center has the option of using an automated speech recognition payment system or a human representative to make the payment. If the user selects to make a payment using a human representative, the representative may, at some point, transfer the user into the automated speech recognition payment system. If the user has already been authenticated, he may not need to re-authenticate himself to the system. If the user selects to make a payment the automated system, and then gets transferred to a human representative during the payment process, the representative may, at some point, transfer the user into the automated speech recognition payment system. Again, if the user has already been authenticated either by the system initially or by the representative, he may not need to re-authenticate himself to the system.

column12: METHOD AND SYSTEM FOR FORMING CUSTOM SHOE INSOLES
column13: The present invention includes a method for forming a custom-made insole including the step of positioning a foot to be measured on a scanning station. The scanning station includes at least one laser unit which is passed along an undersurface of the foot. The undersurface of the foot is scanned by the at least one laser scanning unit which measures the detected surface coordinates of the undersurface. The measured surface coordinates are processed and transmitted to a computer. A milling station, in communication with the scanning station and computer, includes a milling assembly for forming the custom-made insole. The computer controls the operation of the milling assembly based upon the coordinates determined by the at least one laser scanning unit.

column13: PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To provide a method which can progress and monitor an instruction in a processor by preparing a circuit, etc., that can operate to transfer a 1st or 2nd reason code to a 3rd stage by means of a 1st or 2nd execution unit serving as a 2nd stage. SOLUTION: If a dispatch unit serving as a 1st stage stops its operation and cannot dispatch the instructions, a 1st execution unit serving as a 2nd stage receives no Job in a step 801. Then the processing proceeds to a step 803 to decide whether the 1st execution unit can produce its result. Therefore, the 1st execution unit carries out a division operation that requires plural cycles and can produce its result as soon as the division operation is over. Then in a step 804, the 1st execution unit transfers the result of the division operation (e.g. a 1st reason code) to an end unit serving as a 3rd stage.

column12: Method for making contacts to integrated circuits.
column13: @ A composite self-alignment back-etch/lift-off technique is used to obtain masks for patterning integrated circuit device contacts. Proximity effects adverse to the device characteristics are minimized. On the intermediate circuit structure (1, 2, 3) a lift-off resist stencil (5) is patterned with windows exposing areas that are critical with respect to proximity effects. After deposition of a contact metal layer (6) in the exposed areas a back-etch resist stencil (7) is patterned over selected positions of the contact metal to protect the underlying contact regions of the integrated circuit structure. The contact metal not covered by the back-etch stencil is then etched, leaving the desired contact configuration. Finally, the lift-off stencil (5) and the back-etch stencil (7) are removed.

column12: System and method monitoring instruction progress within a processor
column13: A processor operable for processing an instruction through a plurality of internal stages will produce a result of the processing of the process at each stage or a reason code why the stage was unable to process the instruction. The result or the reason code will then be passed to a subsequent stage, which will attempt to process the instruction. The second stage will forward the reason code when it cannot produce its own result and it is idle. The second stage will create its own reason code when it is not idle but cannot produce a result, and will forward this reason code.

column12: Method and system for sychronizing mobile devices
column13: A protocol for synchronizing data is provided. Additionally, a system and method of using the protocol are also provided. The protocol allows responses to be grouped with commands in a single XML document. It provides a command for requesting a single object be sent without requiring that all unsynchronized objects be sent. It provides a command for specifying how many objects at a time should be sent and a response that indicates that more objects are available to be sent. It provides a means for arbitrarily extending the protocol in application-specific ways. It provides a means for sending updates while requesting that no updates be sent back.

column12: METHOD AND SYSTEM FOR FORMING CUSTOM SHOE INSOLES
column13: The present invention includes a method for forming a custom-made insole including the step of positioning a foot to be measured on a scanning station. The scannin g station includes at least one laser unit which is passed along an undersurface of the foot. The undersurface of the foot is scanned by the at least one laser scanning unit which measures the detected surface coordinates of the undersurface. The measured surface coordinates are processed and transmitted to a computer. A milling station, in communication with the scanning station and computer, includes a milling assembly for forming the custom-made insole. The computer controls the operation of the milling assembly based upon the coordinates determined by t he at least one laser scanning unit.

column13: An online valve monitoring system to monitor valve operation and sense the wear senses operational characteristics of a valve and provides a diagnosis of aberrations in the characteristics. Sensors (24,31,34,32,36), coupled to a valve (20), supply sensor signals to a data acquisition system (40,42) to be transmitted to a remote location. An I/O processor (44) at the remote location receives the sensor signals and a diagnostic processor (46) extracts characteristic features from the sensor signals as deviations from baseline data for the valve (20). Use of multiple sensors increases the confidence of the diagnosis which combined with the known trend line of historical data permits scheduling of preventive maintenance.

column12: DEVICE FOR BOXING WOUND COIL OF FILAMENTARY MATERIAL
column13:
PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To provide a method and an apparatus for packaging wound coils of filamentary material in a container.

SOLUTION: The apparatus has a boxing instrument for the wound coils of filamentary material, an end processing section, and a collapsible mandrel. In a first station the filamentary material is wound on the end processing section. A second station has a turret mechanism, a movable rear plate, a bottom plate and an inclined portion. A boxing station is displaceable to the second station to receive the wound coil from the mandrel. The boxing station receives an exploded box arranged on the bottom plate with the rear plate of the box being folded, and has a means for folding two oppositely disposed side plates of the box. The boxing station also has a means for folding flaps of the box to bond and seal them. A payout tube inserting means for inserting a payout tube in a payout hole of the wound coil through a payout hole in the top plate of the box includes means for grasping the free end of the wound coil and withdrawing it through the payout tube.

Said annular slits are the smaller diameter openings of truncated channels, formed between the internal and external shells of stacked conical internal insert members.

column12: Ring oscillator for temperature or voltage sensing
column13: Methods and circuits are disclosed for measuring temperature and/or voltage using ring oscillators. In an example implementation, temperature and/or voltage are determined using an iterative measurements of a ring oscillator. The ring oscillator oscillates with a different voltage-temperature response in each of the first, second and third modes. In each iteration, a first set of indications of frequency are determined for a ring oscillator in a first mode, a second mode, and a third mode. A coarse temperature estimate and a coarse voltage estimate of the ring oscillator are determined based on the indications of frequency measured in a first iteration. A more accurate temperature estimate and a more accurate voltage estimate of the ring oscillator are determined as a function of a second set of indications of frequency measured in a second iteration, the coarse temperature estimate, and the coarse voltage estimate.

column12: Dropping pin non-contact liquid transfer method
column13: A method for transferring drops of liquid carried on a dropping pin onto a substrate to form an ordered array of drops thereon comprises transfer of the liquid without contact of the dropping tool with the substrate, either directly or indirectly via the drop of liquid. This transfer method may involve use of a pin pressure wave, such as generated by a mechanical, piezoelectric or electromagnetic effect, or acceleration then rapid deceleration of the pin. The pin may have a internal capillary (103, fig.10) and reservoir (105, fig.10). Also disclosed is a method in which a pin with an internal capillary and reservoir is impacted on a substrate (fig.12) to transfer liquid droplets to the substrate. Also disclosed is transfer method comprising use of a pressure wave in a pin with capillary and reservoir to transfer liquid droplets to a substrate. Also disclosed is the use of a pin with a regions of varying affinity to liquid, separated by a topological discontinuity.

column12: Non-destructive testing of nuclear fuel rods
column13: Both gadolinia nuclear fuel rods and urania fuel rods are non-destructively tested to determine the enrichment concentration of the fuel pellets therein by serially conveying the gadolinia rods and the urania rod along separate test channels through an active scanner where they are irradiated from a common neutron souce, and the neutron-induced gamma ray emissions are counted as a measure of the enrichment concentrations at a multiplicity of points distributed along the rod length. The enrichment counts are corrected for background radiation, variations in fuel density, and, in the case of gadolinia rods, for gadolinia content by passing these rods through a magnetometer.

column13: A plate assembly for a heat exchanger includes a first plate, a second plate, and an intermediate plate arranged between the first and second plates. The intermediate plate is joined to the first and second plates at peripheral edges to create a sealed periphery of the plate assembly. Corrugations of the intermediate plate provide crests and troughs that are in contact with inwardly facing surfaces of the first and second plates. The plate assembly can be configured as a battery cooling plate heat exchanger to transfer heat from a battery to fluid flowing through the plate assembly.

The tool may be used for planing, turning or shaping operations and the bit may be secured to a milling cutter body for use as a face milling cutter. The sleeve may be of a non-circular matching shape with the bore of the bit to facilitate the indexing of the bit to present successive cutting edges to a workpiece.

column12: Multiprocessor system with fiber optic bus interconnect for interprocessor communications
column13: In a data processing system of the type having multiple processor units coupled to one another by a bus means for interprocessor communications there is provided a fiber optic interconnection system to interconnect the bus means of multiple processor sections to one another, thereby allowing groups of the processor units to be physically spaced from one another. The fiber optic interconnect system includes, for each multiprocessor unit section functions to receive messages communicated on the interprocessor bus of that section for receipt by a destination processor of the other section, format the message for fiber optic transmission, and transmit the message; and circuitry for receiving messages on the fiber optic link, scheduling the message for transmission to the destination processor, and maintaining that scheduling in the face of receipt of another message for the same processor unit. The fiber optic interconnect system includes means for configuring the system to identify which processor units are in which section and, when more than two sections are interconnected by the fiber optic link, provide information as to the shortest route to the destination processor from a section.

column12: METHOD FOR MAKING CONTACTS TO INTEGRATED CIRCUITS
column13: @ A composite self-alignment back-etch/lift-off technique is used to obtain masks for patterning integrated circuit device contacts. Proximity effects adverse to the device characteristics are minimized. On the intermediate circuit structure (1, 2, 3) a lift-off resist stencil (5) is patterned with windows exposing areas that are critical with respect to proximity effects. After deposition of a contact metal layer (6) in the exposed areas a back-etch resist stencil (7) is patterned over selected positions of the contact metal to protect the underlying contact regions of the integrated circuit structure. The contact metal not covered by the back-etch stencil is then etched, leaving the desired contact configuration. Finally, the lift-off stencil (5) and the back-etch stencil (7) are removed.

column12: Segmented rigid plate belt transport with a high motion quality drive mechanism
column13: A vacuum transport includes a segmented, rigid or solid articulated belt combined with a vacuum plenum in each segment of the belt. Using a rigid segmented belt with a vacuum plenum connected to each segmented belt section eliminates ordinarily encountered drag friction in conventional vacuum transports by reducing the force necessary to move the belt with media thereon while simultaneously improving the motion quality of the move by driving the articulated rigid belt from the top side of the belt in a flat section.

column12: Delivery system and method for self-centering a proximal end of a stent graft
column13: A method for implanting a prosthesis centrally within a curved lumen includes loading a prosthesis into a delivery sheath, advancing the sheath in a patient towards the curved lumen to place at least the proximal end of the prosthesis within the curved lumen, and centering the proximal end of the prosthesis and/or the distal end of the sheath within the curved lumen. In a first advancing step, the outer catheter containing the inner sheath is advanced together towards the curved lumen to a location proximal of the curved lumen and, in a second advancing step, the inner sheath containing the prosthesis is advanced into the curved lumen to place at least the proximal end within the curved lumen while the outer catheter substantially remains at the location. After centering, the proximal end of the prosthesis is deployed centered within the curved lumen.

column12: APPARATUS, SYSTEM, AND METHOD FOR MANIPULATION OF NESTED STAMPED PARTS
column13: An apparatus for rotating an inner stamped part with respect to an outer stamped part is provided. The inner stamped part is nested within an aperture formed within the outer stamped part. The apparatus includes a plurality of grippers that include at least a first gripper positioned at a first edge of the inner stamped part and a second gripper positioned at a second edge of the inner stamped part opposite to the first edge. The plurality of grippers is configured to grip the inner stamped part at the first edge and the second edge, respectively. The plurality of grippers is further configured to rotate the gripped inner stamped part about an axis of rotation. The axis of rotation intersects the first gripper and the second gripper. The plurality of grippers is also configured to open to release the inner stamped part.

column12: sistema de integração e método de auto-centragem de uma extremidade proximal de um implante de sonda
column13: SISTEMA DE INTEGRAçãO E MéTODO DE AUTO-CENTRAGEM DE UMA EXTREMIDADE PROXIMAL DE UM IMPLANTE DE SONDA Um método para implantar de forma centralizada uma prótese dentro de um lúmen curvado que inclui o carregamento de uma prótese em um invólucro de integração, inserir o invólucro em um paciente em direção ao lúmen curvado para colocar pelo menos a extremidade proximal da prótese dentro do lúmen curvado, e centralizar a extremidade proximal da prótese e/ou a extremidade distal do invólucro dentro do lúmen curvado. Em uma primeira etapa de introdução, o cateter exterior contendo o invólucro interno é introduzido junto em direção ao lúmen curvado para uma posição proximal do lúmen curvado, e em uma segunda etapa de introdução, o invólucro interno contendo a prótese é introduzido no lúmen curvado para colocar pelo menos a extremidade proximal dentro do lúmen curvado enquanto o cateter externo permanece substancialmente na posição. Após a centralização, a extremidade proximal da prótese é disposta de forma centralizada dentro do lúmen curvado.

column12: DELIVERY SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR SELF-CENTERING PROXIMAL END OF STENT GRAFT
column13: PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To provide a delivery system and method for self-centering a proximal end of a stent graft.SOLUTION: The delivery system includes: a distal end and a guidewire catheter; an apex release catheter slidably disposed about the guidewire catheter, and an apex capture device. The apex capture device includes a distal capture portion fixedly connected to the distal end of the guidewire catheter and a proximal capture portion fixedly connected to the distal end of the apex release catheter and having fingers extending toward the distal capture portion in a distal direction. The both captured portions are formed so as to hold proximal apices therebetween, and together, define a stent captured state in which the proximal apices of a proximal stopper and a stent are received in an interior cavity. Thereby, the proximal apices are captured and a support bar is extended from between the fingers of the proximal capture portion in a radial direction and the interior cavity along the longitudinal axis is approximately closed off by the distal capture portion.

column12: DELIVERY SYSTEM AND APEX CAPTURE DEVICE
column13: A method for implanting a prosthesis centrally within a curved lumen includes loading a prosthesis into a delivery sheath, advancing the sheath in a patient towards the curved lumen to place at least the proximal end of the prosthesis within the curved lumen, and centering the proximal end of the prosthesis and/or the distal end of the sheath within the curved lumen. In a first advancing step, the outer catheter containing the inner sheath is advanced together towards the curved lumen to a location proximal of the curved lumen and, in a second advancing step, the inner sheath containing the prosthesis is advanced into the curved lumen to place at least the proximal end within the curved lumen while the outer catheter substantially remains at the location. After centering, the proximal end of the prosthesis is deployed centered within the curved lumen.

column12: SYSTEM FOR AND METHOD OF PRODUCING ARYLAMINE COMPOUND
column13:
PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To provide a new method in which arylamines can be continuously produced using Buchwald reactions even in a large-scale production.

SOLUTION: The method of producing arylamine compound includes reacting an amine compound with an arylhalide compound in a continuous plug flow reactor in the presence of a base and a palladium catalyst having a ligand so that an arylamine compound can be produced. In this method, all products and by-products remain solubilized.

column13: An online valve monitoring system senses operational characteristics of a valve and provides a diagnosis of aberrations in the characteristics. Sensor signals from the valve are transmitted to a diagnostic processor which extracts characteristic features from the sensor signals as deviations from baseline data for the valve or operational values for predetermined reference operations. An expert system applies a rule base to the characteristic features or operational values; the expert system being updated in a largely automatic process by collecting operational and maintenance data which is linked together to produce data-derived rules. Criteria are defined for comparing the data-derived rules and pre-existing rules in the rule base. All data-derived rules meeting the criteria and, if only single-valued conclusion parameters are in the rules, the pre-existing rules meeting the criteria are placed on the agenda. Each of the rules on the agenda are compared with all of the other rules or, when a multi-valued conclusion parameter is used in the criteria, with all of the pre-existing rules in a pool of rules meeting the criteria. For each pair of rules, if the conclusions conflict and the premises are not mutually exclusive (or independent if a multi-valued conclusion parameter is used in the criteria), the pair of rules are placed on a conflict list which is output to a human expert for evaluation to produce an updated rule base.

column12: Non-destructive testing of nuclear fuel rods.
column13: Both gadolinia nuclear fuel rods (12b) and urania fuel rods (12a) are non-destructively tested to determine the enrichment concentration of the fuel pellets therein by serially conveying the gadolinia rods and the urania rod along separate test channels through an active scanner where they are irradiated from a common neutron source (40), and the neutron-induced gamma ray emissions are counted as a measure of the enrichment concentrations at a multiplicity of points distributed along the rod length. The enrichment counts are corrected for background radiation, variations in fuel density, and, in the case of gadolinia rods, for gadolinia content by passing these rods through a magnetometer (26).

column12: Delivery system and method for self-centering a proximal end of a stent graft
column13: A method for implanting a prosthesis centrally within a curved lumen includes loading a prosthesis into a delivery sheath, advancing the sheath in a patient towards the curved lumen to place at least the proximal end of the prosthesis within the curved lumen, and centering the proximal end of the prosthesis and/or the distal end of the sheath within the curved lumen. In a first advancing step, the outer catheter containing the inner sheath is advanced together towards the curved lumen to a location proximal of the curved lumen and, in a second advancing step, the inner sheath containing the prosthesis is advanced into the curved lumen to place at least the proximal end within the curved lumen while the outer catheter substantially remains at the location. After centering, the proximal end of the prosthesis is deployed centered within the curved lumen.

column12: System and Method for Producing Arylamine Compounds
column13: Improved methods for making hole transport molecules (HTMs) that are incorporated into imaging members, such as layered photoreceptor devices, to increase the photoreceptor's "hole mobility," or its ability to move charge, across its charge transport layer (CTL). Embodiments pertain to a continuous process for making N,N-diphenyl-4-biphenylamine and a system for performing the same. The process involves reacting an amine, usually an arylamine, with an arylhalide, in the presence of a base and a ligated palladium catalyst in a continuous plug flow reactor, wherein all products and by products remain solubilised. Maintenance of solution may be achieved by addition of a cosolvent such as an ether or a phosphonium based ionic liquid before the reaction is initiated.

column12: Sistema de suministro y dispositivo de captura de ápice
column13: Un sistema (600) de suministro para suministrar y desplegar una prótesis que comprende un estent o injerto de estent dentro de una aorta (700) natural o enferma mediante la alineación de la prótesis con la curva de la aorta, que comprende: a) un lumen (620) del alambre guía que tiene un extremo distal y que define un interior que se extiende a lo largo del eje longitudinal del lumen (620) del alambre guía; b) un lumen (640) de liberación de ápice que tiene un extremo distal y que está dispuesto de forma deslizante sobre el lumen (620) del alambre guía; y c) un dispositivo (634) de captura de ápice, que comprende i) un cabezal (636) de ápice distal conectado de manera fija al extremo distal del lumen (620) del alambre guía, teniendo el cabezal (636) de ápice distal una porción distal, y radios que incluye cada uno una superficie circunferencial externa, una superficie (639) distal colocada de manera enfrentada a una dirección distal que está dispuesta en un plano perpendicular al eje longitudinal y que define una porción superficial de tope, y una superficie (641) proximal que es ahusada, por lo cual la superficie (641) proximal se extiende a lo largo de una línea que se cruza con el lumen (620) del alambre guía proximal a la superficie (639) distal de unos radios en un ángulo oblicuo, y ii) un cuerpo (638) del ápice proximal conectado de manera fija al extremo distal del lumen (640) de liberación del ápice y que tiene dedos que se extienden hacia el cabezal (636) del ápice distal en una dirección distal, definiendo los dedos una cavidad interior conformada para recibir en ella los radios, definiendo juntos el cuerpo (638) del ápice proximal y el cabezal (636) del ápice distal una abertura para sostener los ápices (32) proximales de los estents (30) entre los mismos, y en el que una circunferencia externa de los radios del cabezal distal y los dedos, cuando los dedos se superponen a los radios, definen un espacio radial que tiene un espesor inferior al diámetro de los ápices proximales de los estents, definiendo de este modo un estado capturado de estent de los estents en el que los radios y los ápices proximales de los estents se reciben en la cavidad interior y restringiendo de este modo los ápices proximales de los estents de la prótesis, mientras que los puntales de los estents de la prótesis se extienden hacia fuera radialmente entre los dedos del cuerpo (638) del ápice proximal, y el cabezal (636) del ápice distal cierra la cavidad interior a lo largo del eje longitudinal del lumen (620) del alambre guía.

column12: NON-DESTRUCTIVE TESTING OF NUCLEAR FUEL RODS
column13: Both gadolinia nuclear fuel rods (12b) and urania fuel rods (12a) are non-destructively tested to determine the enrichment concentration of the fuel pellets therein by serially conveying the gadolinia rods and the urania rod along separate test channels through an active scanner where they are irradiated from a common neutron source (40), and the neutron-induced gamma ray emissions are counted as a measure of the enrichment concentrations at a multiplicity of points distributed along the rod length. The enrichment counts are corrected for background radiation, variations in fuel density, and, in the case of gadolinia rods, for gadolinia content by passing these rods through a magnetometer (26).

column13: An online valve monitoring system senses operational characteristics of a valve and provides a diagnosis of aberrations in the characteristics. Sensor signals from the valve are transmitted to a diagnostic processor which extracts characteristic features from the sensor signals as deviations from baseline data for the valve or operational values for predetermined reference operations. An expert system applies a rule base to the characteristic features or operational values; the expert system being updated in a largely automatic process by collecting operational and maintenance data which is linked together to produce data-derived rules. Criteria are defined for comparing the data-derived rules and pre-existing rules in the rule base. All data-derived rules meeting the criteria and, if only single-valued conclusion parameters are in the rules, the pre-existing rules meeting the criteria are placed on the agenda. Each of the rules on the agenda are compared with all of the other rules or, when a multi-valued conclusion parameter is used in the criteria, with all of the pre-existing rules in a pool of rules meeting the criteria. For each pair of rules, if the conclusions conflict and the premises are not mutually exclusive (or independent if a multi-valued conclusion parameter is used in the criteria), the pair of rules are placed on a conflict list which is output to a human expert for evaluation to produce an updated rule base.

column13: 1,187,504. Synthetic resin compositions. BRITISH INDUSTRIAL PLASTICS Ltd. 26 April, 1967 [29 April, 1966; 7 Dec., 1966], Nos. 18869/66 and 54769/66. Headings C3P and C3R. A thermosetting moulding composition comprises an unsaturated polyester resin, a copolymerizable monomer and a finely divided filler, at least part of which, providing at least 10 wt. per cent of the composition, is a substantially water-insoluble metal borate. The composition may also include a fibrous reinforcing filler and a mould lubricant. The resins are condensates of a glycol, and optionally a polyol, e.g. pentaerythritol, and a mixture of an unsaturated dibasic acid, e.g. maleic or fumaric, and a saturated dibasic acid, e.g. phthalic or adipic. Specified comonomers are styrene, vinyl toluene, diallyl phthalate and a mixture of styrene and methyl methacrylate. Specified borates are those of Ca, Mn, Zn, Sr, Cu<SP>++</SP> and Mg; the hydrated borates are preferred but basic borates may also be used. Other finely divided fillers mentioned are Mg, Zn and Ca carbonates, slate powder, magnesium fluosilicate, NH 4 , Ca and Mn sulphates, Mg and Ti oxides, Ca oxalate, Zn sulphite, boric acid, Ni hydroxide, asbestos, quartz, fluorspar, Na metaphosphate, tribasic zinc phosphate, dicyandiamide, Ca cyanamide, talc, guanamines, melamine and aminoplast resins, e.g. urea- or melamineformaldehyde resins which may be spraydried. The fibrous reinforcing filler may be glass, asbestos, nylon, polyester, polyacrylonitrile, polyvinyl alcohol or acetate or polypropylene. The mould lubricant may be stearic acid or zinc or magnesium stearate. In examples, the resin is 2 parts of propylene glycol maleate phthalate in 1 part styrene catalysed with 1À5% benzoyl peroxide and the fillers are Ca metaborate, Zn borate, anhydrous Zn borate, basic Mg borate or Mn borate together with “ in. glass fibres, polypropylene or nylon flock and various of the other fillers mentioned above and alumina and antimony oxide; zinc stearate is included in all examples. The compositions are useful for moulding electrical apparatus, e.g. insulators and arc-suppressing devices.

column12: Medium system for forming physical three-dimensional objects
column13: Method, system and computer program directed to generating a physical three-dimensional color-accurate objects based on a 3D computer-based colour model using printed layers of media. The printed layers also known as 2D page images or slices are formed from a 3D computer-based color model into 3D cross-sectional components 550, which retain the color information of the model 510. The colour information can be included in a plan image corresponding to the cross-sectional segments. The page images are printed to form cross-sectional prints which can be layered and trimmed to shape the prints into a colour accurate physical object that represents the model. Preferably, a space between an inner perimeter and outer perimeter form an area of colour when printed and revealed when trimmed.

column12: MEDIA-BASED SYSTEM FOR FORMING THREE-DIMENSIONAL OBJECTS
column13: Embodiments described herein are directed to generating physical three-dimensional color-accurate objects based on a 3D computer-based color model using printed layers of media. Embodiments can slice a 3D computer-based color model into 3D cross-sectional components, which retain the color information of the model. The 3D cross-sectional segments can be converted into 2D page images and the color information can be included in a plan image corresponding to the cross-sectional segments. Embodiments can print the page images to form cross-sectional prints which can be layered and trimmed to shape the prints into a color accurate physical object that represents the model.

column12: MEDIENBASIERTES SYSTEM ZUM BILDEN VON DREIDIMENSIONALEN OBJEKTEN
column13: Hier beschriebene Ausführungsformen sind auf das Erzeugen von physikalischen dreidimensionalen farbgetreuen Objekten auf Basis eines computerbasierten 3D-Farbmodells unter Verwendung von gedruckten Medienschichten gerichtet. Ausführungsformen können ein computerbasiertes 3D-Farbmodell in 3D-Querschnittskomponenten schneiden, die die Farbinformationen des Modells beibehalten. Die 3D-Querschnittsegmente können in 2D-Seitenbilder umgewandelt werden, und die Farbinformationen können in ein Draufsichtbild, das den Querschnittsegmenten entspricht, aufgenommen werden. Ausführungsformen können die Seitenbilder drucken, um Querschnittdrucke zu bilden, die geschichtet und getrimmt werden können, so dass die Drucke in ein farbgetreues physikalisches Objekt geformt werden, das das Modell repräsentiert.

column12: Using product and social network data to improve online advertising
column13: Methods and apparatus for improving word-of-mouth online advertising are provided. Construct a social network including multiple users based on the users' social network data and optionally further based on the users' demographical and/or other personal information. Categorize the users in the social network with respect to a type of product in terms of their propensity to adopt the type of product and to influence others in the social network in adopting the type of product. column12: MEDIA-BASED SYSTEM FOR FORMING THREE-DIMENSIONAL OBJECTS
column13: PURPOSE: A media based system forming 3D objects is provided to use color information embedded in a 3D computer based model in computing environment, thereby generating physical rendering which an accurate color for the model is implemented. CONSTITUTION: A media based system distinguishes a 3D model and determines a medium which a physical object is generated(700,702). The media based system slices the 3D model based on the medium up to the number of cross section segments by a slicing unit of a disintegration system and converts the cross section segments of the model into page images(704,706). The media based system generates an ordered stack of page images and prints the page images by a printing system(708,710). The media based system layers and trims the page images(712). [Reference numerals] (700) Distinguish a model; (702) Determine a medium; (704) Slice the model for generating cross section segments; (706) Convert the cross section segments into page images; (708) Generate an ordered stack of the page images; (710) Print the page images; (712) Layer and trim the page images for generating a physical object with accurately implemented color corresponding to the model

column12: Steering column structural support system and method
column13: An integrated steering column structural system for distributing a load of a steering column within a vehicle is disclosed. The structural system includes a steering column bracket for retaining the steering column and for distributing the steering column load throughout the vehicle. The structural system further includes a plurality of load distribution components for receiving the load of the steering column and ultimately distributing the load to a vehicle structural frame. The steering column bracket utilizes a plurality of pathways through which to distribute the load of the steering column to the load distribution components.

column12: SYSTEM FOR MEDIUM BASE FOR CREATING THREE-DIMENSIONAL OBJECT
column13: PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To create a physical three-dimensional object by accurately reproducing colors on the basis of the color model of a 3D computer base.SOLUTION: A physical object is created by accurately reproducing colors by using the layer of a medium to be printed. That is, the color model of a 3D computer base is sliced into 3D cross-sectional segments, and the color information of the model is stored in those cross-sectional segments. Thus, the 3D cross-sectional segments can be converted into a 2D page image, and the color information can be included in a plane image corresponding to the cross-sectional segments. Thus, the page image can be printed, and a cross-sectional printed matter can be formed. Those cross-sectional printed matters are piled up and trimmed so that the object can be created.

column12: Media-Based System For Forming Physical Three-Dimensional Objects
column13: Method, system and computer program directed to generating a physical three-dimensional color-accurate objects based on a 3D computer-based colour model (400, fig.4) using printed layers of media. The printed layers also known as 2D page images (610, fig.6) or slices are formed from a 3D computer-based color model into 3D cross-sectional components 550, which retain the color information of the model 510. The colour information can be included in a plan image (612, fig.6) corresponding to the cross-sectional segments. The page images are printed to form cross-sectional prints which can be layered and trimmed to shape the prints into a colour accurate physical object that 'represents the model. Preferably, a space between an inner perimeter (626, fig.6) and outer perimeter (628,fig.6) form an area of colour when printed and revealed when trimmed.

column12: Method and apparatus for provisioning software on a network of computers
column13: An apparatus and method for provisioning software on a network of heterogeneous computers in a network. The provisioner receives a list of packages and deployment scope of the packages, then checks each node for installed applications and records dependency and potential application conflicts. In addition, the provisioner measures a plurality of network and node metrics. Based on the dependency information, conflict information, and metrics, one or more nodes are selected and software is provisioned and/or removed in accordance with the dependency and conflict information.

column12: SYSTEMS, METHODS AND APPARATUS FOR DIFFERENTIAL AIR PRESSURE DEVICES
column13: Described herein are various embodiments of differential air pressure systems and components for differential air pressure systems. The air pressure systems comprise a chamber for receiving at least a portion of a user's body. Pressure in the chamber can be changed to adjust force on the user's body. Described herein are various methods and related structures for sealing a user into a pressurizable chamber. Also described herein are various methods and related structures for changing the shape and/or height of the chamber. Described herein are various types and configurations of chambers and support structures for chambers. Also described herein are various methods and related systems for treating various conditions using the differential air pressure systems, including but not limited to obesity, cardiac disease, multiple sclerosis, cerebral palsy, or Down Syndrome.

column12: Cooling motor controller with a motor including wedge-shaped heat sinks
column13: Embodiments of cooling a motor controlling using a motor are disclosed. In some embodiments, a system includes an electric motor including at least one rotor with integrated features positioned and configured to pull air into and through the electric motor. The system also includes at least one motor controller each comprising a heat sink positioned in an air intake path from a source of air to the electric motor. A method of manufacturing the system includes arranging at least one motor controller and at least one electric motor, coupling the at least one motor controller and at least one electric motor via a flexible duct, and adapting the arrangement of the at least one motor controller and the at least one electric motor to passively provide cooling via airflow through the at least one motor controller and at least one electric motor in proportion to a load on the at least one electric motor.

column12: Method and system for providing conferencing services
column13: An approach is provided for supporting multi-media conferencing. Textual information (e.g., text associated with a presentation) is received for display during a conference session to multiple participants. For a particular participant, configuration information corresponding to the participant specifies language assistance for the textual information. Language assistance involves augmenting the textual information according to the configuration information for comprehension of the textual information by the particular participant. In one embodiment, the augmented textual information includes language translation of the textual information. Additionally, the augmented textual information can encompass definitions of terms, including acronyms. The augmented textual information is forwarded for display to the participant during the conference session.

column12: Cooling motor controller with a motor with duct
column13: Embodiments of cooling a motor controlling using a motor are disclosed. In some embodiments, a system includes an electric motor including at least one rotor with integrated features positioned and configured to pull air into and through the electric motor. The system also includes at least one motor controller each comprising a heat sink positioned in an air intake path from a source of air to the electric motor. A method of manufacturing the system includes arranging at least one motor controller and at least one electric motor, coupling the at least one motor controller and at least one electric motor via a flexible duct, and adapting the arrangement of the at least one motor controller and the at least one electric motor to passively provide cooling via airflow through the at least one motor controller and at least one electric motor in proportion to a load on the at least one electric motor.

column12: SYSTEMS, METHODS AND APPARATUS FOR CALIBRATING DIFFERENTIAL AIR PRESSURE DEVICES
column13: Methods, apparatus, and systems for calibrating differential air pressure systems are described. The methods, apparatus, and systems may be adapted for physical training of an individual, e.g. as a training tool to improve performance or as a physical therapy tool for rehabilitation or strengthening. The differential air pressure systems comprise a chamber for receiving at least a portion of a user's body. In one embodiment, a method for calibrating a differential air pressure system for predicting effective body weight of a user versus system pressure is described. In certain variations, the methods, apparatus and systems may comprise adjusting pressure in the system until one or more force values are reached. The methods described herein may comprise determining a relationship between body weight force and pressure, allowing the user to set a pressure or a parameter correlated with pressure to achieve a desired effective body weight.

column12: Method and apparatus for scheduling jobs on a network
column13: An apparatus and method for scheduling a job process on at least one node in a server data processing network. The scheduling is based on a state of at least two nodes in the network as well as a cost metric of installing a required application on at least one of the nodes in the network of nodes. The apparatus and method gathers metrics indicating properties associated with at least two nodes on the network, the metrics including a presence of an application necessary for running the process. A first cost factor for scheduling the process on a node in the network having the application necessary for running the process is compared with a second cost factor for scheduling the process on a node in the network that does not have the application necessary for running the process. Finally, a node in the network is selected for scheduling the process.

column12: METHOD AND APPARATUS FOR PROVISIONING SOFTWARE ON NETWORK OF COMPUTER
column13:
PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To provide an apparatus and method for provisioning software on a network of heterogeneous computers in a network.

SOLUTION: The provisioner receives a list of packages and deployment scope of the packages, then checks each node for installed applications and records dependency and potential application conflicts. In addition, the provisioner measures a plurality of network and node metrics. Based on the dependency information, conflict information, and metrics, one or more modes are selected and software is provisioned and/or removed in accordance with the dependency and conflict information.

column12: REACTIVE, LOW MOLECULAR WEIGHT, VISCOUS POLY(1-OLEFINS) AND COPOLY(1-OLEFINS) AND THEIR METHOD OF MANUFACTURE
column13: Catalysts and processes are described to make low molecular weight, essentially terminally-unsaturated, viscous poly(1-olefin) or copoly(1-olefin) having a high terminal vinylidine content from a feed stock containing one or more 1-olefin and other volatile hydrocarbon liquids using a Ziegler catalyst made from a Group IVb metallocene and an aluminoxane cocatalyst, particularly bis(cyclopentadienyl) and bis(indenyl) titanium(IV), zirconium(IV) or hafnium(IV) compounds and methylaluminoxane. A particularly useful feed stock is a refinery stream containing 1-olefins and isobutylene which is used to make polyisobutylene. The reactive, essentially terminally-unsaturated, viscous poly(1-olefin) or copoly(1-olefin) can be functionalized to make a number of products useful as sealants, petroleum additives, adhesives, and the like by reacting the terminal vinylidine linkage with an aromatic, an epoxidation agent, a silylation agent, maleic anhydride, carbon monoxide and hydrogen, hydrogen, a halogen, a hydrohalogen, and the like.

column12: ADAPTIVE LOAD LIMITING SEAT BELT RETRACTOR
column13: An adaptive load limiting seat belt retractor particularly adapted for motor vehicle applications The retractor provides multiple levels of load limiting through the use of a pair of internal torsion bar elements The torsion bar elements control the tension force on the seat belt webbing dunng an impact in a manner which provides desirable crash management characteristics The retractor can be switched between high and low load limiting modes through activation of a pyrotechnic pretensioner When the pyrotechnic pretensioner is not activated, the retractor provides a low load level characteristic Pretensioner activation switches the retractor into a high load level operating condition A high load limiting level is provided when the pretensioner is not activated if the spindle rotation exceeds a limited level in the low load limiting condition

Based on the dependency information, conflict information, and metrics, one or more nodes are selected and software is provisioned and/or removed in accordance with the dependency and conflict information.

column12: Systems, methods and apparatus for calibrating differential air pressure devices
column13: Methods, apparatus, and systems for calibrating differential air pressure systems are described. The methods, apparatus, and systems may be adapted for physical training of an individual, e.g. as a training tool to improve performance or as a physical therapy tool for rehabilitation or strengthening. The differential air pressure systems comprise a chamber for receiving at least a portion of a user's body. In one embodiment, a method for calibrating a differential air pressure system for predicting effective body weight of a user versus system pressure is described. In certain variations, the methods, apparatus and systems may comprise adjusting pressure in the system until one or more force values are reached. The methods described herein may comprise determining a relationship between body weight force and pressure, allowing the user to set a pressure or a parameter correlated with pressure to achieve a desired effective body weight.

column13: An adaptive load limiting seat belt retractor particularly adapted for motor vehicle applications. The retractor provides multiple levels of load limiting through the use of a pair of internal torsion bar elements. The torsion bar elements control the tension force on the seat belt webbing during an impact in a manner which provides desirable crash management characteristics. The retractor can be switched between high and low load limiting modes through activation of a pyrotechnic pretensioner. When the pyrotechnic pretensioner is not activated, the retractor provides a low load level characteristic. Pretensioner activation switches the retractor into a high load level operating condition. A high load limiting level is provided when the pretensioner is not activated if the spindle rotation exceeds a limited level in the low load limiting condition. A degressive load limiting feature may be provided to cause load limiting to begin at a higher level than the high load limiting level, and then step down the high load limiting level.

column12: Method and apparatus for scheduling jobs on a network
column13: An apparatus and method for scheduling a job process on at least one node in a server data processing network. The scheduling is based on a state of at least two nodes in the network as well as a cost metric of installing a required application on at least one of the nodes in the network of nodes. The apparatus and method gathers metrics indicating properties associated with at least two nodes on the network, the metrics including a presence of an application necessary for running the process. A first cost factor for scheduling the process on a node in the network having the application necessary for running the process is compared with a second cost factor for scheduling the process on a node in the network that does not have the application necessary for running the process. Finally, a node in the network is selected for scheduling the process.

column13: 1,140,841. Cutting tools. PRODUCTION ENG. RESEARCH ASSOCIATION OF GREAT BRITAIN. 21 Jan., 1966 [24 Jan., 1965; 1 Nov., 1965], Nos. 34571/64 and 46098/65. Headings B3B, B3K and B3L. In a method of machining such as turning, milling and planing in which a slice-like cutter bit 12 secured to a holder 11 is fed into a workpiece transversely to the cutting direction, the bit has a cutting edge formed at the juncture of its face with its side wall and is orientated in relation to the workpiece so that its face is the clearance face 15 and the side wall 14 forms the rake face, the angle of obliquity of the cutting edge to the cutting direction being the maximum which achieves effective cutting. The angle of obliquity is defined as the angle between a tangent to the cutting edge and the direction of cutting. In addition to the orientation of the cutting bit as set out above, the bit may also be inclined to the axis of the holder. The bit is secured to the holder by means of a screw and a split sleeve (see Specification 1,140,843) and may be invertable and indexable so as to present a new cutting edge to a workpiece when required. The various forms of cutter bit (see Specifications 1,140,842 and 1,140,844) may be circular or polygonal and the cutting edges may be formed by a plurality of successive arcuate portions. Also a narrow land may be provided along part or all of the cutting edge depending on the shape of the bit and the cutting conditions required.

column13: The invention exploits stabilization of the non-covalent donor ubiquitin interaction with E2 enzymes, including Cdc34-ubiquitin interaction. column12: METHOD AND SYSTEM FOR PROVIDING CONFERENCING SERVICES
column13: An approach is provided for supporting multi-media conference (109). Textual information (e.g., text associated with a presentation) is received for display during a conference session to multiple participants. For a particular participant, configuration information corresponding to the participant specifies language assistance (109b) for the textual information. Language assistance involves augmenting the textual information according to the configuration information for comprehension of the text information by the particular participant. In one embodiment, the augmented textual information includes language translation of the textual information. Additionally, the augmented textual information can encompass definitions of terms, including acronyms (1117). The augmented textual information is forwarded for display to the participant during the conference session.

column13: 1,014,171. Floor conveyers. BRITISH UNITED SHOE MACHINERY CO. Ltd. Dec. 18, 1961 [Dec. 20, 1960; Aug. 5, 1961; Sept. 22, 1961], Nos. 43750/60, 28517/61 and 23950/61. Heading B7L. A floor conveyer, e.g. for use in shoe factories, comprises a plurality of wheeled carriages adapted to carry shoes, and a conveyer for conveying the carriages through a number of work areas, each carriage comprising an engaging device adapted to be engaged by the conveyer, and a forwardly extending bumper linked to the engaging device and adapted to move it out of engagement with the conveyer when the bumper encounters an obstruction, and wherein the conveyer comprises, in one work area, a pool position and a number of operating positions, with, e.g., an identical shoe machine at each position, the conveyer also comprising, in another work area, e.g. a single different shoe machine, the conveyer being provided with a stop device at the pool position movement of which from a first condition to a second condition releases the leading carriage of the pool from the stop device, which carriage is then conveyed towards the operating positions; a stop device at each operating position, which device is movable between a first condition in which it stops a carriage being conveyed by the conveyer and a second condition in which it allows carriages to pass: a release device at each operating position, which, when a carriage arrested by the associated stop device is removed from operable relationship to the conveyer causes the stop device to return from its first to its second condition; and a signal device associated with each operating position which on operation causes the stop device at the pool position to move from its first to its second condition releasing a carriage from the pool, which is then conveyed to the operating position with which the signal device is associated, the signal device also causing the stop device at its associated operating position to move to its first condition in which it arrests the carriage being conveyed, which carriage is readily removable from operable relationship to the conveyer by an operator. The conveyer comprises a horizontal rectangular channel 4, Fig. 2, extending through the work areas one side of the channel being provided by a rail 3 which guides the carriages when they are being conveyed. An endless chain 14 is located in the channel, which chain comprises fixed upstanding members to engage with the conveying device of a carriage. The stop device at the pool position, Fig. 7.- The stop device at the pool position comprises a first stop member 20 and a second stop member 22 both extending along and close to the channel 4 of the conveyer. With the stop device in its first condition the first member 20 is in an upper position in which it extends obliquely upwards providing an inclined surface 20P, and the second member 22 is in a lower position in which it extends horizontally. With the device in its second condition the member 20 extends horizontally and the member 22 extends obliquely upwards. With the stop device in its first condition, the leading carriage of the pool is held stationary by the first member 20, the engaging device of the carriage being held in an upper position out of engagement with the chain 14. When the stop device moves to its second condition the engaging device of the leading carriage is able to move into engagement with the chain 14 and the carriage is conveyed thereby. Subsequent carriages are retained by the second member 22 until the device is returned to its first condition when the carriages are all moved forwardly until the leading carriage is arrested by the first member 20. The remainder of the pool of carriages are held one behind the other with their engaging devices being held clear of the chain 14, by collision of their front bumpers with the next preceding carriage. The end portions of the stop members 20, 22 comprise abutments 24S, 50S, respectively, which positively prevent the engaging device of a carriage from moving past the stop members. The members 20, 22 are pivoted at 25, 48, respectively, and are actuated by solenoids 38, 62. The solenoids when energized move pivoted members 30, 56, respectively, which act on cam surfaces 42, 66 on the members 20, 22 against the action of springs 44, 64. The springs normally hold the stop device in its first condition and then when the solenoids 38, 62 are energized the device is moved to its second condition. The stop device and release device at each operating position, Fig. 9.-These stop devices each comprise a stop member 96 extending along and close to the channel of the conveyer and movable between a lower second condition in which it extends horizontally, Fig. 9, and an upper first condition in which it extends obliquely upwards providing an inclined surface. When the stop device is in its first condition a carriage reaching the device is arrested, its engaging device being moved upwardly out of engagement with the chain 14, by engagement with the inclined surface. The end portion of the member 96 comprises an abutment 98S which arrests the carriage and prevents the engaging device of the carriage from moving past the stop member. The release device comprises an elongated catch member 122 pivotally mounted at 123 on the stop member 96 and adapted to operate two microswitches 134, 136. When the stop member 96 is in its lower condition an upper surface of the member 122 extends above the member 96 and the microswitches are not operated. When the stop member is in its upper position, the upper surface of the member 122 still extends above the member 96 and the microswitches 134, 136 are not operated until the engaging device of a carriage is held by the abutment 98S. This depresses the member 122 and causes it to operate the microswitches 134, 136, and this operation causes the stop device at the pool position to return from its second to its first condition. On removal of the carriage held by the stop member 96 from operable relationship to the conveyer the elongated member 122 is released and this causes the stop member 96 to return to its lower condition. The member 96 is pivoted at 100 and is operated by a solenoid 116. When the solenoid is energized it moves a pivoted member 110 against the action of a spring 118 to raise the member 96, the member 110 engaging with a cam surface 117 on the member 96. The microswitches 134, 136 are operated by set-screws 130, 132, respectively, arranged so as to operate the microswitch 136 slightly before the switch 134. The stop member at the other work area referred to, is a fixed member extending obliquely upwards providing an inclined surface, and provided with an abutment at its upper end (Fig. 11a, not shown). Its action is similar to that of the stop members at each operating position. The carriages 2, Figs. 1, 2.-Each carriage comprises a frame 78, and a base 83 fitted with four casters 77. Each carriage is provided with an engaging device 18, comprising an L-shaped member 84 pivoted to the base 83. A hollow cylinder 94 is fixed to the forward end of the member 84. A rod 88 is rotatably mounted in the cylinder 94 and to the forward end of this rod is fixed a cross-shaped member 92 with four arms 107 which abuts against the forward end of the cylinder 94. A ratchet member 90 is mounted slidably on the rod 88 and is held by a spring 97 in contact with the notched rear end of the cylinder 94. The spring 97 also acts as a shock-absorber for the member 18. The member 92 is rotatable clockwise only between four positions in which two of its arms 107 are vertical. A bracket 121 depending from the base 83 serves to steady the member 84. When a carriage is moved into operable relationship to the conveyer, the carriage is pushed by use of fixed handles 74 so that the lowermost arm 107 engages the rail 3, whereupon the member 92 is rotated through 90 degrees. This brings another of the arms 107 into engagement with the chain 14, and one of the horizontal arms 107 is in a position to engage with the stop devices of the conveyer. A pivoted latch member 105 on an arm 103, Fig. 2, is also provided and under the action of a spring 111 this engages the rail 3 and steadies the carriage 2 whilst it is being conveyed. Each carriage is provided with a front bumper 79, comprising upper and lower plates 75, 85, respectively. The lower end of the plate 85 is hinged on a rod 89 to the frame of the carriage and a horizontal hinge 87 is provided between the plates 75, 85. The upper end of the plate 75 carries a rod 91 which is mounted for up and down sliding movement in slots 95 in the frame. A rod 82 links the engaging device 18 with the rod 91 and when the bumper 79 engages an obstruction, e.g. the rear bumper 76 of the preceding carriage, the rod 91 is moved upwardly and this moves the device 18 out of engagement with the chain 14. Twelve shoe holders 200 are secured to the frame of the machine. Alternative engaging device, Fig. 6.-This device comprises a member 222 fitted to a rod 88<SP>1</SP> fitted in place of the rod 88 of Fig. 2, which rod 88<SP>1</SP> is not rotatable. The member 222 has a cam surface 226 which will ride over the rail 3<SP>1</SP> as the carriage is moved into operable relationship to the conveyer. When the member 222 is raised by a stop device it is still not clear of the rail 3<SP>1</SP> and thus the carriage cannot drift away from the conveyer. A handle (not shown) is provided to lift the member 222 clear of the rail 3<SP>1</SP> when it is desired to move the carriage away from the conveyer. Means for steadying the carriages during movement, Fig. 16.-Two robust abutment members 404, 406 fitted with rollers 414, 416, respectively, are secured to the base of a trolley so that they are disposed on the other side of the rail 3 from the engaging device 319 which is held from side to side movement by depending brack

column13: A semi-conducting device comprises a planar, superconducting surface (10) which has been formed to define an input branch (12), an output branch (14) and a clock line (6) extending transversely between the input and output branches (12, 14). The device has a line (18) along which the superconductivity has been destroyed. This line (18) extends generally in the direction of the clock line (6) to define respective areas (L1, L2, L3) adjacent the input branch (12) and the output branch (14). The inductance of the area (L1) adjacent the input branch is greater than the inductance of the area adjacent to the output branch (14). A first Josephson junction (J1) is provided adjacent to the input branch (12) and a second Josephson junction (Js) is provided adjacent to the output branch (14) and extends transversely of the clock line (6). The first and second Josephson junctions are formed by direct electron beam irradiation.

column12: Connecting insert for a terminal assembly
column13: A terminal assembly includes a terminal having a wire barrel and a mating segment configured to be mated to a mating component. The terminal assembly includes a shuttle assembly configured to be coupled to an end of a wire. The shuttle assembly includes a connecting insert defining a wire chamber configured to receive an exposed conductor of the wire. The connecting insert has a retention tab extending into the wire chamber. The retention tab is configured to interfere with and retain the wire in the wire chamber. The connecting insert is received in the wire barrel of the terminal and the connecting insert is configured to be crimped between the wire barrel of the terminal and the exposed conductor of the wire when the wire barrel is crimped around the connecting insert and the wire.

column13: A train control system for controlling trains traveling in a track network including tracks with signals associated therewith. The system includes an on-board track database, a positioning system and an on-board control system. The on-board control system receives position data and automatically brakes the train prior to encountering an upcoming signal based upon specified data points. column12: METHOD AND SYSTEM FOR PROVIDING CONFERENCING SERVICES
column13: An approach is provided for supporting multi-media conferencing. Textual information (e.g., text associated with a presentation) is received for display during a conference session to multiple participants. For a particular participant, configuration information corresponding to the participant specifies language assistance for the textual information. Language assistance involves augmenting the textual information according to the configuration information for comprehension of the textual information by the particular participant. In one embodiment, the augmented textual information includes language translation of the textual information. Additionally, the augmented textual information can encompass definitions of terms, including acronyms. The augmented textual information is forwarded for display to the participant during the conference session.

column13: Described are materials for a shoe upper, in particular for soccer shoes, with a particularly low weight. The material includes an inner polyurethane layer, an outer polyurethane layer, and a textile reinforcing layer. The textile reinforcing layer is arranged between the inner polyurethane layer and the outer polyurethane layer. The inner polyurethane layer and the outer polyurethane layer comprise thermoset polyurethane. The textile reinforcing layer comprises apertures through which the inner polyurethane layer and the outer polyurethane layer are connected to each other.

column12: sistema e método de controle de trem
column13: sistema e método de controle de trem a presente invenção refere-se a um sistema de controle de trem (10) para controlar trens (tr) em uma rede ferroviária incluindo linhas ferroviárias com sinais associados com as mesmas. o sistema inclui uma base de dados embarcada (12), um sistema de posicionamento (16) e um sistema de controle embarcado (18). o sistema de controle embarcado (18) recebe dados de posição e automaticamente freia o trem (tr) antes de se deparar com um sinal se aproximando com base em pontos de dados especificados. o trem (tr) não é automaticamente frenado se certas condições não foram atendidas. um método para controlar um trem percorrendo uma rede de ferrovias também é revelado.

column13: A method, executed in a computer system, for opening an electronic market for trading of a security is described. The method includes receiving by the computer system eligible orders and quotes for the security traded in the electronic market and disseminating an order imbalance indicator indicative of predicted trading characteristics of the security at the open of trading. The method also includes determining by the computer system a price or prices at which the maximum shares would be executed and determining which price would minimize any imbalance of eligible orders and executing at least some of the eligible orders at the determined opening price.

column13: An example tap off box is provided that includes a housing, a circuit breaker, a door, and a breaker actuator. The housing includes walls forming an internal enclosure. The circuit breaker is disposed within the housing. The door is secured to the housing to define a housing assembly, the housing assembly enclosing the circuit breaker. The breaker actuator includes a distal end and a proximal end, the distal end coupled to the circuit breaker within the housing assembly, and the proximal end extending outside of the housing assembly. The breaker actuator is capable of being moved at the proximal end to selectively toggle the circuit breaker from at least an ON position to an OFF position.

column12: Dual Stage Pretensioning and High Pay-In Capacity Pretensioning Retractor
column13: A seat belt retractor for use in seat belt restraint systems. The retractor incorporates dual rotopretensioner units and adaptive load limiting characteristics. Preferably, the rotopretensioners are positioned on opposite ends of a retractor spool for driving the spool for pretensioning rotation. A first pretensioner may be activated alone to provide pretensioning rotation. In one embodiment of the invention, if the second pretensioner is not activated, the system will be engaged to provide a given belt load limiting characteristic. A second rotopretensioner may be fired either after the first pretensioner is fired to increase pay-in capacity or to activate a different load limiting characteristic for the retractor.
